On 12 April 2021, 80 vials of Moderna vaccine (Lot# 046A21A) were discovered to have been improperly handled and stored at the facility.  These vials were determined to have been at room temperature from 22 March to 6 April.  Before this temperature excursion discovery on the afternoon of the 12th, those doses were regrettably administered to 806 patients on 7 and 12 April at the vaccination site at the training center.  After conferring with immunization experts and the manufacturer, it was confirmed that the efficacy of the doses in question could not be guaranteed.  This facility has assembled a clinical team to contact each of these patients, disclose the information, and offer them re-vaccination.  Re-vaccination efforts are beginning on 20 Apr 2021.  Initial guidance was that a VAERS needed to be completed for each patient impacted and that effort was started.  However, subsequent opinion from an employee at the CDC was that one VAERS report to describe the incident was sufficient.  This VAERS is to cover the incident.  If there are any follow-on questions/concerns, please contact me.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Several days after recieving my Moderna vaccine, I began to feel itchiness in my feet. Within a few hours, the itchiness spread to my hands (both the tops of my hands and my palms). The itchiness spread to my wrists as well. By the morning of April 17th, I had swollen, red hives on my hands, wrists and feet. The itching was coupled with a burning feeling. Benadryl and Calamine lotion did not help. As the day continued, the hives spread to my ankles, knees and elbows. In the morning on Monday, April 19th I felt stiff (didn't know this was part of my reaction until my doctor asked me if I felt like my joints were stiff--I was too itchy to feel concerned about it), the bottoms of my feet were painful, and I could barely touch anything with my hands without it hurting. As the day continued, I became so uncomfortable between the itchiness and burning I decided to see my doctor.
LAB_DATA: My doctor looked at all of the places on my body where hives were present. He asked me about my joints and I said that morning I had felt stiff (my feet felt stiff at this point at the doctor's). He sent me to get some bloodwork done (I remember CBC and a COVID antibody test) and I went right from the doctors. He prescribed methylprednisolone and ceturizine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 31JAN2021: -Received her first shot of Moderna vaccine in right deltoid with subsequent 24h sore right shoulder but zero other symptoms  25FEB2021: -Received her 2nd shot of Moderna vaccine in left deltoid. No acute symptoms.   26FEB2021: -Noticed diffuse joint pain throughout ALL joints, exhaustion, severe headaches, nausea  -Took Advil at night for these symptoms and felt better for several hours before resurgence of symptoms  27FEB2021: -Slept all day and then felt completely better, good appetite, watched her daughter?s volleyball tournament  -That night, noted a red circle (non-raised, not itchy) at the site of the left deltoid injection  28FEB2021: -Red circle had increased in size to the size of a quarter but she felt fine otherwise -By the night time, the left deltoid had swollen to softball size and became itchy   01MAR2021: -Increased size of left deltoid swelling and persistent itching, went to see PCM and got topical hydrocortisone and Benadryl   Over the first week of March, her daughter (who rooms with parents but downstairs) developed COVID-19 and was isolated as best as possible away from mother for 10 days. The patient noted that the arm just kept getting worse (continued progression of swelling with small itchy bumps that popped and oozed fluid, developed pain in left elbow with severe swelling. Lesions were painful to touch). Was visiting with her PCM every Monday and saw her multiple times who gave her an ?antibiotic cream? which the patient reports she could not use because it was too large of an area. On 12MAR, she was given more Benadryl, an EpiPen, prednisone taper (starting at 60mg per day), and Keflex which the patient started taking. Her PCM said if she did not get better in 24h to go to the ED.   13MAR2021: The patient came to the ED and was assessed and released with Atarax and doxycycline and she continued the prednisone given by her PCM. She had taken two doses of doxycycline and three doses of Atarax before heading to the ED once again on 15MAR2021.   15MAR2021: Came to the ED again after noticing at work that her face was red and her tongue was swelling in the back of the throat. She was driven to the ED by her husband. She was given an EpiPen in the ED quickly. Her heart rate became fast, she reported, but the EpiPen resolved her itching of the face/neck, the redness dissipated, and her tongue felt ?back to normal.? She also received Solumedrol 125mg IV, Benadryl 25mg IV, and 1L normal saline. Several hours later, her tongue swelling and face itching and red rash returned, and she received an additional EpiPen IM injection and then Valium 5mg PO which resolved her symptoms and helped calm her down. She was then admitted for 2 nights in the step down for observation. She reports this was an unremarkable admission and she felt fine after the second EpiPen injection. The only symptom she reported was a bad headache the whole admission which was not relieved well with ibuprofen and acetaminophen. She said she had some peeling of skin on her left arm as well.   17MAR2021: Discharged home, headache persisted. Rash on face/neck and tongue swelling was completely gone. The swelling and lesions and pain on the left upper arm had improved but pain and swelling in the left arm were still present. She took a steroid taper for a week along with Pepcid and Benadryl daily.   From 17MAR2021 until today 20APR2021, her left arm swelling has slowly improved. She saw her PCM twice in this timeframe. The first time, she gave pt. 15 days of 10mg prednisone PO daily and Pepcid and Benadryl because her left arm swelling had resurged. This regimen helped reduce the symptoms. The second time she went to see her, she increased her Benadryl to 50mg PO nightly to reduce itching of the left arm and was given another 9 days of 5mg PO daily prednisone which she finished 20ARP2021. The additional prednisone was given because the patient had reported a resurgence of the symptoms of itching and swelling of the left arm.   The itching and the swelling of the left arm completely resolved by 07APR and she went back to her job on 13APR.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, zinc, vitamin D, oral contraceptive, proton pump inhibitor

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/19, I was light headed, body ached, arm sore where injection was, had 100.7 temp.  It all subsided on 4/20.

Admission HPI: Right-sided chest pain began 2 days prior to admission (3/19) after getting out of car, without identifiable trigger. Pain was sharp, pleuritic, and worst with movement; didn't feel it when still. Pain not responsive to ibuprofen or heating packs. Reported 30-60 seconds of self-resolving heart racing during ocular migraine which has been his baseline for years. Not associated with SOB (at rest or with exercise), palpitations, presyncope, or syncope. No viral URI symptoms, N/V, or rash. He did receive his 2nd Moderna COVID vaccine about 1 week PTA, followed by 36hrs of fevers, chills, and body aches. Given persistence of pain, Patient asked his parents to present to urgent care.   In UC, he was noted to tachycardic with CXR with bibasilar atelectasis and b/l effusions, per report. Given continued tachycardia, decision was made to transfer to ED to r/o PE.      In ED, tachycardic to 104-116 and tachypneic 22-26. Had one episode of tachycardia to 182 iso ocular migraine. Endorsed chest pain but points to R middle abdomen when asked where worst. Exam was unremarkable. He received 1 dose of morphine which reduced pain from 10/10 to 0/10. Labs notable for leukocytosis (14.61), thrombocytopenia (422), elevated d-dimer (1.56), and elevated CRP (5.6). Otherwise normal chem and coags. COVID/RVP negative. CXR unremarkable. CTPA showed scattered PEs in b/l lower lobes with small pulmonary infarct in RML. No evidence of right heart strain. Heme was consulted who recommended starting him on lovenox and sending lupus anti-coagulant. Cardiology was consulted who recommended EKG, BNP, and troponin, all of which were normal and reassuring against right heart strain. ECHO was therefore deferred to the AM. The decision was made to admit.   Upon arrival to the floor, Patient was tachycardic 114 and tachypneic to 22, otherwise stable vitals. He denied any pain since morphine. Denied any unexpected weight loss; reports that car ride was short. Mom reports that Patient has been less active d/t cold weather and baseball being on hold. Denies family or personal history of clots. Last seizure ~13 years ago.  Hospital Course: (3/21 - 3/22)  Patient was admitted to the hematology service. He was therapeutically anticoagulated with LMWH injections and his anti-Xa level prior to discharge was 0.92. (goal 0.5-1.0) Lower extremity ultrasound with Doppler showed patent veins and no evidence of DVT and upper extremity ultrasound showed no evidence of DVT, though there was potential evidence of collateralization seen in mid and distal third of right subclavian vein and left internal jugular vein. Since this was an unprovoked PE, a full thrombophilia workup was sent and will be followed up by the outpatient hematology clinic. Cardiology consulted regarding possibility of right heart strain and the tachycardia during migraine episodes. Echocardiogram performed on 3/22 was technically limited but showed no gross abnormalities. The cardiology team requested a repeat echo scheduled outpatient for 1-2 months after discharge.
LAB_DATA: As above.    Relevant Diagnostic Images/Studies:  Chest X-ray 3/20: 20:22 Lungs: Lung volumes are low. There are bibasilar opacities, compatible with atelectasis. No focal consolidation. Heart/mediastinum: Cardiac contours are obscured, but likely top normal in size. Pleural effusion: None. Pneumothorax: None. Osseous/soft tissue structures: Normal. Included upper abdomen: Gas distended bowel loops in the left upper quadrant are partially imaged. SYMPTOM_TEXT: DAY ONE  April 15, 2021. On Thursday April 15th at 10:00 a.m. I received the first dose of the Covid 19 vaccine.   They gave me the shot in my left arm.  Within about 5 seconds, I started feeling nauseated and light headed like I was going to pass out.  I asked to just sit there for awhile because I did not feel stable to stand up and go to the waiting area.  I stayed seated for about 1-2 more minutes then the paramedics took me to the Medical area in a wheelchair.    The paramedics checked my vitals.  My blood pressure was 135 over ?? I don't remember.  I told the medic my BP is normally 98/58.   She said my BP was elevated.   My pulse was in the high 80's.  My temperature was 98.6 and my oxygen was 100.  I started getting pain and pressure going up the back of my neck, into my head, eyes and ears.  It was very painful and throbbing pressure.  I felt dizzy and really high.   It felt like I was floating on the top of the ceiling and the people were off in a distance.  I was really woozy.    I then got diarrhea.   The nausea continued but I did not throw up.  At times my thinking was spacey, so I talked to the paramedic to help me stay grounded.  I narrated what was happening in my body.  They did a glucose finger prick test because of my spaceyness, but it was normal.   It was like my whole system was freaking out.  I was there and then not there, feeling like I was floating.    These symptoms continued for about 90 minutes and getting worse.  The paramedics offered me to go to the hospital, but I thought eventually I would be fine.  I did not want to go to the hospital and have a huge medical bill.   At around 90 minutes, I started having pain in my heart left side, under my left breast on my left shoulder.  The paramedics did an EKG and did not find anything but some irregular heartbeats.  The heart beats felt like BA BOOM, then my heart would do a cartwheel.  BA BOOM and another cartwheel.    At this time, my husband arrived and took me to the hospital emergency room because the pain in my heart was getting worse.  I stayed in the hospital emergency room until around 5:00pm on April 15th. They did another EKG and some lab work and did not find anything but low thyroid.  I continued to feel drunk, nauseated, pain pressure and throbbing in my head neck, ears and eyes, diarrhea, and like I was High and going to pass out.    The chest pain in my heart was off and on.  It felt like muscle cramping in my heart, under my left breast and the left shoulder.  I also got a pain in my left groin area, then behind my left knee.  It was a sharp and throbbing pain for about an hour in each location, but eventually went away.    While in the Emergency room, they tried to give me Ativan.  I asked what it was for and they said Anxiety.  I said I wasn't anxious; I was just having a reaction to my first Covid 19 vaccine.  I said I did not want it because my body was already struggling to handle the Covid 19 vaccine.  They said the doctor prescribed it.  I said I had not seen a doctor, and they said it is protocol.  The nurse then came in and wanted to give me a shot for nausea and I said no, I don't want any more chemicals in my body, it is really having a hard time already with the Covid vaccine.    I went home, was wiped out, still feeling drunk/woozy/high, also nauseated, diarrhea, very dizzy, had a hard time walking.  The pain, throbbing in my head, neck, ears and eyes was still there.  By this time, I could not find clear thoughts, and could not make sense of things.   I was very agitated and at the same time exhausted and only wanted to sleep.    DAY TWO April 16, 2021 I woke up with a smashing head ache, neck ache, back ache and general feeling like Crap.  The nausea and diarrhea were still there and had woken me in the middle of the night.   I felt like a truck had hit me.  I stayed in bed all day and tried to eat and drink as much as I could.  I drank a lot of water that day.  I felt horrible, but was able to stand without feeling like I was going to fall over.  Had trouble finding clear thoughts at times.  Still felt out of it and had chest pain off and on.  Also had the BA BOOM heart beats and cartwheels in my heart.    DAY THREE  April 17, 2021 Very similar to day two.  I felt weak, nauseated, diarrhea, pain all over, jittery, not able to have clear thoughts at times.   It felt like my body was still on RED ALERT!!!    I also had very shallow breathing on day  2, 3, 4 and 5.  It tired me and I panted just getting up to go to the restroom.  I am able to eat fine and keep food down.  BA BOOM hear beats and cartwheels in my heart have lessened.    DAY FOUR April 18, 2021 I felt a little better and made the mistake of thinking I was getting over the reactions and did too much.  Shortness of breath.   DAY FIVE April 19, 2021 I feel horrible again, Nausea is really strong as well as the diarrhea.  I am feverish, sweaty and shaky.  Shortness of Breath. Tight in my chest. I just took my temperature and it is normal, although I am hot, sweaty, feel feverish and shaky.  I am exhausted.  The headache is still here as well as the pains in my neck, ears and eyes.   The aches in my body are still here.  I have no energy.  A wave of emotions is also here and I am weepy and crying.    This is no fun.   I am able to eat food OK and drink lots of water to counteract the diarrhea.    DAY SIX April 20, 2021 Shortness of breath, very tight in my chest, having to take Benadryl and use my rescue inhaler to keep my breathing open.   Feverish, chills, shakey, hot.   Temperature 97.0   Blood pressure 90/66 Pulse 70.  I feel like crap, just wiped out.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: First dose was administered on 1/22/21 (lot#EL3302) after which I began with hormonal fluctuations consistent with pre-menstrual symptoms (would be normal for someone 2 Yrs POST-menopausal) On 2/15/21, following my second dose on 2/12/21, I experienced the onset of what could only be described as menses, which, although extremely light, continued for 3 days.  Coincidentally, on 2/19/21, I had an annual exam scheduled at which I mentioned this odd occurrence.  I was advised that post menopausal bleeding is not normal and I needed follow up tests.  I am relatively informed and explained that my experience was not random bleeding, it was truly a menstrual period with all symptoms relating to such, but decided to follow through with testing to be sure.  I had an ultrasound performed on 2/25/21 which noted an endometrial stripe of 5mm (1mm wider than ?normal?) and a hysteroscopy was scheduled and performed on 4/9/21.  Biopsies taken and visual inspection showed NO abnormalities whatsoever and my bleeding occurrence was considered idiopathic.  In speaking with the physician, she refused to acknowledge that the Covid vaccine could have had anything to do with the event, but several others I know in healthcare have stated that there is a possible link and there is documentation to support.

4/4: Woke up Easter Sunday with the following symptoms: sweats, chills, uncontrollable shaking, fatigue, dizziness, nausea, and shortness of breath. Went to Urgent Care, but it was closed for the holiday, so instead went to ER. See Item 19 for details. I was discharged within an hour because there was nothing seriously wrong with me, doctor wrote it off as a stomach bug and ordered me to rest and hydrate.  4/4 - 4/10: Virtually every day for this week went the exact same. I would wake up between 6-7am, feel nauseous, weak, no appetite, and shaking. Walking around my apartment would leave me utterly exhausted. I would nap from 9am-12pm, then again from 2-4pm. Ate very little, drank water and sports drinks when awake. Breathing was still shaky. Occasional diarrhea.  4/10: Although slightly less ill than the previous 6 days, I still felt weak, shaky, and exhausted. I went back to Urgent Care this time, and the doctor examined me. She noted my left ear was very inflamed and suspected an ear infection. She prescribed me a week of amoxycilin and told me to rest and eat bland foods.  4/12: After 2 days on the antibiotics, some of my symptoms cleared. I was no longer shaking or having shortness of breath, and although still tired, I did not sleep for half the day as I had the previous week. My appetite was not fully there yet, and in the mornings of this week I would wake up feeling nauseous for about 2 hours. On this day 4/12 my period also started, which is unusual. It was not due to start until around April 17th. My period is very regular and light due to being on birth control, so I consider this abnormal. The flow was also very heavy.   4/17: Heavy flow of my period slows significantly and is now just a slight pink/brown color. I only need a liner to contain it. This is also my last day of antibiotics, so I buy a probiotic supplement in the hopes that it will help settle my gut.  4/17-present (4/20): The morning nausea and lack of appetite are still present despite being off the antibiotics. Occasional discomfort in abdomen/chest. Unexplained muscle soreness in hips, legs, back, and chest. My bowel movement schedule has also completely changed. Normally I do not experience a bowel movement until late morning, after 10am. But for the past 2 weeks I have been woken up around 5:30am with a sudden urge. At the beginning of my illness it was diarrhea but now it has transitioned to slightly more solid feces. It is not really diarrhea anymore.
LAB_DATA: 4/4 Emergency Room Visit: Doctor ordered a urine test, blood test, and abdominal CT scan. All of these tests came back completely normal. No fever, but elevated blood pressure (130/80 ish) and heart rate (99bpm while sitting/laying).  4/8: Took a rapid COVID-19 test, was negative.  4/10 Urgent Care Visit: Elevated BPM and blood pressure, same as in the ER. Doctor prescribed amoxycilin for ear infection.
OTHER_MEDS: Sronyx (birth control) - taken regularly, no late or missed doses in the last 6 months

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 29 y/o female, past medical history of HTN (unmedicated) and Arrythmia (type unknown), who presents with left facial, neck and left upper extremity numbness onset set shortly after vaccination. Patient states that this is her 1st dose in the two-dose series, and she has never had a reaction to vaccinations in the past. NP and Paramedics at patient side. Water was provided to patient and legs elevated. Patient facial features symmetrical with no facial droop, equal strength and pulses to the upper extremities. Stroke scale negative. Patient also states a weird iron like taste to her mouth, a very strong taste but states that she can swallow without difficulty. Patient noted to be Hypertensive (155/103 R) on initial vitals, all other vitals within normal limits. Repeat vitals showed that patient remained Hypertensive (156/91, 145/103, 158/106, 160/84). Patient was then moved (ambulated to the gurney) and placed behind the partitions for privacy. At this time, EKG was performed with NSR. Patient stated that the numbness to her left arm and neck had resolved but remained with the iron taste to her mouth and slight numbness to her left cheek. Repeat EKG was performed and showed an Arrythmia (per Paramedics). At this time, due to elevated BP and facial numbness Fire Rescue was notified via Police Officer on detail. Hialeah Fire Rescue arrived at the site and assessed patient on the truck. Per Fire Rescue, it was noted on EKG that patient in AFib. Patient declined transport to the ER for further evaluation and signed Against Medical Advice with Fire Rescue and as well with Logistics team and Healthcare workers. Patient was ambulated to her car with the NP at her side. NP advise patient to seek further medical evaluation due to her risk of stroke, worsening arrythmia leading to cardiac event and/or possible death. NP also advise patient to obtain a primary care provider and cardiologist to address her Hypertension and Arrythmia. Patient verbalized understanding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: *Patient was being observed in the patient waiting area post injection given at 11:00am. Had to wait 30 minutes due to prior reaction to MMR in December of 2020. At 20-25 minutes post injection patient started itching with arms and chest becoming red. Nurse and NP observing came over to patient and assessed. They administered Benadryl 25mg due to itching and redness. Advised patient to go home and also take Pepcid to help the Benadryl. Patient drove home immediately and by 12:00pm after looking in mirror lips and lower arms minimally swollen. Patient took another 25mg of Benadryl. No change, skin continues to break out and itch. Right lower forearm begins to swell more. Patient takes a third Benadryl 25mg along with a Prednisone 20mg PO.  After the 75mf of Benadryl total and Prednisone 20mg the reaction gradually subsides, but does not go away 100%. It is manageable at this time.  *Overnight the patient develops dizziness and headache.  *By morning (07:00am on 04/16/2021) the patient is itching minimally, dizzy, has headache, nauseated, and now is experiencing vertigo with what feels like equilibrium imbalance. Patient stays home from work and rests all day. No fever, no SOB, and no other signs at this time.  *Patient continues to show the above signs through Monday, April 19, 2021 with now on Tuesday April 20, 2021 additional signs of night sweats, muscle cramps, and soreness in her legs.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 2AM on Thursday, a severe headache (I would term a migraine based on prior experience) woke me. I had no apparent fever, but my body was stiff and I felt my heart rate was elevated. I drank some water, in case it was dehydration-related, but was unable to fall back asleep. I also experienced some nausea at breakfast but ate toast and had some (caffeinated) tea about 6 AM. Around 7 AM I took two (2) ibuprofen, which dulled the headache slightly. However it persisted into early/late afternoon hours on Thursday. (My customary activities were curtailed somewhat.) Since I have had migraines in the past, I treated this as I treated those: hydrating, taking pain medication as required, remaining quiet, reducing exposure to light and sound, etc. I continued taking two (2) ibuprofen periodically as I felt the need through bedtime Thursday night.  Friday I had periodic headaches (again, attributed them to rebound migraines or just headaches), felt tired, and been a bit 'out of it'. But my systems did not prevent me from functioning. I did repeat the two (2) ibuprofen on Friday night at bedtime.

Mother reports that she had the vaccine, had no symptoms, and then started with a fever that evening of 103.  She was having cold extremities, numbness, tingling of the arms, face, legs.  The fever dropped and went away and was having fatigue and getting winded doing regular activities.  By Monday she continued with the shortness of breath and go increasingly worse as the days went on and also the.  By Wednesday she was having chest pain, numbness and tingling of her extremities and shortness of breath.  She went to the hospital, gave her IVs, says her BP was elevated and sent her home.  Mother told her to sleep and see how she felt.  By Thursday night 4/15/21 she screamed out because she was having chest pains and having chest and pains and not able to straighten out her hand and could not catch her breath.  She was then taken back to the hospital and said that she her BP was high and said that she had the Janssen vaccine, and said that she was hyperventilation due to anxiety.  Once they got her stable and released her again.  Mother asked the doctor if he felt that this was normal, and could see her throat contracting and that she was stable and to go home, and he said yes and that it was anxiety and that sometimes we get ourselves worked up about things and that was causing it.    The daughter has no history of anxiety, no breathing issues.   They did labs and everything was okay, her counts were somewhat off but nothing felt to be abnormal.      She then went to another Hospital as she was still not feeling well, and checked the other reports from the other hospital and they conferred with that information, gave her Valium and sent her home. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a half hour of injection, I experienced pain in my left leg (thigh muscle mostly). Throughout the day the pain spread to my left hip and left calf. Additionally, I felt like my muscles were ?on fire? on the left side of my body. I also felt a ?tingling? in my body, fingers and toes, leg muscles, primarily on left side. (I assumed at that time that this was ?normal?.) About 11 hours after injection, I experienced extreme muscle pain all over my body, lasting for about 12 hours. (Flu-like muscle pain and the feeling that all of my muscles were on fire.) The following day, I began to feel the feeling of pins and needles everywhere but primarily on left leg, thigh and calf.  By Thursday evening (three days following injection), I felt the most severe pins and needles feeling as well as ?itching? primarily in calves and hands and feet. I was so uncomfortable and panicked, I couldn?t sleep. On Friday evening, I felt intense leg pain and ?heat? on left side in both calf and thigh muscle and couldn?t sleep. On Saturday evening and all day Sunday I had a headache which I can?t say was related but caused me great concern. Now, eight days later, most of the pins and needles feeling has subsided but the pain in my left leg (thigh muscle) is at an all time high. Extra strength Tylenol is not helping. I did have a consult with my doctor last Thursday and I called again yesterday and I?m waiting for a call back. (Last Thursday, she agreed that my symptoms were unusual and thought I might need to see a neurologist.) Additionally - my left knee has bothered me and feels like someone hit it with a bat. I?m not sure if this is joint pain?  FYI - I have no apparent swelling in legs, no numbness, no trouble breathing and no significant headache today. I never had a fever or chills. The injection site burned for a few days (mild)  but was never red.
OTHER_MEDS: Iron, vitamin B, vitamin C, vitamin D, Biotin, Allegra
HISTORY: Previous history of high blood pressure.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to Levaquin, Hemp Seed and quinoa   Also allergic to cats, dogs, many animals and unspecified seasonal allergies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After getting the Johnson & Johnson shot at 3:15PM on Saturday (I did pass out at the vaccine clinic approx 2 minutes after receiving the vaccine and had to be escorted to a room to lay down) I developed chills, fever, and aches that night, but that's not what I'm reporting.  Sunday night, I developed painful red spots on my right inner labia. Monday morning, they had multiplied and darkened. I went in and saw my gynecologist, at 2:00PM. By that time they had worsened again. She could not immediately identify it, but swabbed it to test for herpes. She also prescribed an anti-viral, a rotating dose of OTC 600 ibuprofen and 500mg tylenol, and that I should pick up Orajel for topical numbing.  By Wednesday, the herpes test came back negative (as I expected, having never had herpes), and the spots had grown in size and turned into black and grey ulcers that were shedding with necrosis and were extremely painful. In addition, I was experiencing near exhaustion.  Dr. diagnosed them as Lipsh�tz ulcers. A severe immune response to the vaccine. In addition to the antiviral, she prescribed a steroid to help quiet the immune response and a few days worth of Hydrocodone to help with the very acute pain.  As of writing this on 4/20/2021, I am still not fully recovered, although Dr. believes it will be cleared up completely in the next couple of days.
A red line appeared between the bottom of my nose to the top  of my upper lip.

On April 1, 2021 I received the first dosag of the Moderna. I left there and was fine, but on Saturday April 3, I began to swell. It started off looking like an insect bite, but as the day progressed, the bumps became knots that were painful and itchy. On April 4, I was in a lot of pain causing me not to be able to use my left arm so I did a virtual visit with Urgent Care. I was told I was experiencing the "Covid Arm" and to take Benadryl for the itching and bumps and Ibuprofen for the inflammation and pain, and to sit out of work. After a few days of  the Benadryl I experienced the next outbreak on April 6, and I used the virtual visit again, I was taken out of work and told to continue the Benadryl but to take it 3 times a day. Again, Benadryl worked a few days and on April 12th I had another breakout on my face, causing pain, swelling and discoloration. The doctors prescribed Prednisone and continued Benadryl. I took that for 5 days, and on Sunday April 18, I had the most recent breakout. I went to a dermatologist on 4/19 and was given triamcinolone cream, allegra and benadryl. I have to return in 2 weeks to be examined again. This allergic reaction has been ongoing for 19 days, and counting.

Patient received the first Moderna Covid-19 vaccine and a few weeks later he noticed jaundice and hematuria. He was admitted to the Hospital, and was noted to have dramatically elevated eosinophils (26.29 k/uL), elevated creatinine (2.36 mg/dL) and elevated LFTs (AST/AST/Alk Phos/Tbili all up, mostly direct). His eosinophils improved with pulse dose steroids and the diagnostic work up continues. There is diagnostic uncertainty about what caused this dramatic increase in eosinophilia, but it appears temporally related to getting the vaccination. Our working diagnosis is autoimmune vasculitis, but he is also being treated for possible parasitic infection, and will require very close follow-up. 61M with PMHx HTN p/w generalized fatigue, L flank pain, and decreased UOP.   He was in his usual state of health until 5 days prior to admission with onset of general fatigue/sluggishness. This was followed by a few days of dull abdominal pain, watery bowel movements, and increased frequency which spontaneously resolved, though the fatigue persisted. Yesterday evening, he noticed new L flank pain, red urine, and decreased UOP associated with mild dysuria (he describes it as needle-like pain in his urethra) which prompted him to call EMS. Denies fevers/chills/night sweats, myalgias, respiratory symptoms, melena/hematochezia. He's never had pyelonephritis or kidney stones before, no recent urinary instrumentation, antibiotic use, or hospital stays.    He recently received the first COVID vaccine and is due for the second COVID shot on Monday. He lives with his sister and works as a mechanic. He is not on any other medications or supplements. Not currently sexually active.    ED Course Vitals: Temperature: 36.7 �C (98 �F) | Heart Rate: (!) 103 | BP: (!) 169/121 | Respiratory Rate: 18  | SpO2: 96 %  |    | FIO2     | Weight: 104.3 kg (230 lb) Exam: L CVA TTP  Labs: Cr 2.34, bicarb 18, WBC 37, UA w/ 3+ blood, +1 LE, nitrates, >182 RBCs, 32 WBC, no bacteria, no casts Imaging: CT/AP with mild L hydrouretonephrosis, b/l periureteral and perinephric stranding, b/l urothelial thickening Interventions: CTX 1g, ketorolac, 1L LR, morphine    ===================== Hospital Course 4/10-4/16 ===================== #B/l Pyeloureteritis with Eosinophilia c/f Eosinophilic Pyeloureteritis  #B/l L Hydroureter/Hydronephrosis, B/l Perinephric Stranding and Pericystic Stranding #Profound Eosinophilia Pt presented with malaise, hematuria, decreased UOP and markedly leukocytosis with predominant eosinophilia to 26k and was found to have L hydroureter/hydronephrosis, b/l perinephric stranding and pericystic stranding on CT A/P (4/10). Notably has been afebrile and fairly well appearing. Symptoms were preceded by several days of watery diarrhea, cough with sputum production and subjective weight loss. Recently received moderna vaccine, and he was concerned it causes his symptoms.  Underwent extensive workup as below with involvement of multiple services including Renal, Pulm, Rheum, Allergy, ENT, and Cardiology. Had one nasal lesion biopsied by ENT, which was non-diagnostic. Renal bx prelim without clear e/o vaculitis, although obtained after steroids. Negative testing for primary hypereosinophilic syndrome. Extensive w/u notable for ANCA positive at 1:80 with  MPO only slightly elevated (20, uln 19) and PR3 wnl.  cMRI with eosinophilic cardiomyopathy, for which cards was consulted as below. Additionally, toxacara ab positive and schistosoma ab indeterminate, although per ID both schistosomiasis and toxacara infection unlikely. Per rheum, overall felt presentation 2/2 hypereosinophilic syndrome, potentially the eosinophilic stage of EGPA (given low + ANCA, low + MPO) vs.  End organ effects of idiopathic eosinophilia. Briefly received CTX 2g IV qd (4/10 - 4/12) until diagnostics returned. Treated with solumedrol 1g qd x3d (4/11-4/13) transitioned to prednisone 60 mg qd (4/14-) to be continued until rheum f/u, with rapid decline in eosinophilia. Received pre-treatment with PO ivermectin 20 mg before steroids. Treated with flonase nasal spray, symbicort and albuterol for respiratory symptoms. Deferred cyclophosphamide, with consideration of IL-5 or IL-5R targeted biologics as an outpatient. Treated with atovaquone for PCP ppx. Per ID, treated with praziquantel (for schistosomiasis) and albendazole (for toxacara) out of an abundance of caution, although low c/f visceral larva migrans given lack of compatible imaging findings and no known exposure to dogs and cats or schistosomiasis given remove travel history.  Data - CT A/P (4/10): Mild L hydroureteronephrosis with b/l periureteral and perinephric stranding and b/l urothelial thickening. Pericystic stranding. - 4/11 CT Chest with parasinus mucosal thickening and sclerotic 1 cm lesion likely benign lesion or bone island - 4/11 CT Face with parasinus mucosal thickening and small fluid levels and sclerotic ovoid 1 cm lesion in neck of right mandible potentially representing benign fibro osseous lesion or bone island - PFT with severe obstruction and elevated FeNO c/w eosinophilic infiltration - Heme review of smear with normal Eos - Echo TTE with LVH nl EF 52% - Vitamin B12 >2000 - Urine Eos undetectable after steroids - SPEP with polyclonal hypergammaglobulinemia  - Sinus Bx equivocal - ANA, ANCA (1:80; MPO 20, PR3 3), ESR (128), CRP (66), RF (<13), C3 (82, slightly low), C4 (10) - IgE 355 - Aspergillus IgG and IgE <19 - HIV non-reactive - RHP with CHIP mutation which will need f/u - FIP1L1 negative - Schistosoma ab equivocal - Strongy ab negative - Toxacara ab positive - Leptospira ab negative - Tryptase wnl - RHP notable for CHIP mutation as below - BCR-ABL negative - FIP1L1-PDGFRA negative - peripheral blood flow cytometry unremarkable   #AKI on CKD #Nephritic syndrome #Urinary retention/hydronephrosis Cr 2.34 on admission.  Baseline Cr unknown but Cr was 1.5 (OSH BI) and urine alb:Cr was elevated to 36 in 6/2018, at which time CKD was thought to be 2/2 untreated HTN. Now presented with persistent hematuria, HTN and proteinuria with UCx without e/o infection, all favoring nephritic process. Renal and urology consulted MALB/CCR 994.5. CT scan with hydronephrosis, felt to be eosinophilic pyelonephritis. Pt underwent uncomplicated renal bx 4/14 (after steroids) which showed preliminary very mild focus of interstitial nephritis with scattered eosinophils and immunofluorescence evidence suggestive of a mild immune complex-mediated disease without current activity. EM pending. He was treated with sodium bicarb 1300 mg bid. Hematuria improved but did not resolved by time of discharge. Cr on discharge 1.6, close to baseline of 1.5 in 2018.    #Sclera Icterus #CBD Dilation on CT #Elevated LFT Sclera icteric and CBD dilation on RUQUS to 1.8cm with gallbladder sludge and small gallstones. MRCP with diffuse intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation to the level of ampulla, with associated ductal and gallbladder wall edema, complex material in the gallbladder lumen and CBD, and confluent periportal lymphadenopathy. No obstructing stone or discrete mass. Findings likely represent cholangitis such as eosinophilic cholangitis in light of severe eosinophilia.. No documented LFTs here, but OSH (BI) records indicate normal LFTs and viral hepatitis studies in 6/2018. Repeat Hep B non-reactive non immune, HCV non immune, HAV non-reactive.  BIli remained stable and ALT and AST continued to rise after initiation of steroids. GI was consulted. RUQUS 4/15 with dopplers with persistently dilated CBD to 1.4 cm with sludge in CBD but with patent portal vein and hepatic veins. Anti smooth muscle ab positive on day of discharge; antimitochondrial ab pending. LFT uptrending at time of discharge, although patient declined to stay inpatient for further workup. LFT at discharge ALT 194, AST 114, ALP 262, TBili 6.3, DBili 5.3. ERCP to be considered as an outpatient.     #HTN SBP on admission 160-180. History of HTN, not on any home anti-hypertensives. Per BI records, he was prescribed amlodipine 10/valsartan 160 in 6/2019, but pt reports self-discontinuation after ~2 doses. BP remains poorly controlled. Likely related to potential nephritic syndrome or renal infiltration by eosinophils, likely with contribution of high dose steroids. While inpatient, treated with hydralazine, labetalol, carvedilol, and amlodipine. BP regimen on discharge amlodipine 10 mg qd, carvedilol 25 mg qd. Avoiding ARBs and ACEI per Renal, although will likely need to add once AKI resolved.    #Microcytic Anemia Patient with drop in Hct from 14.1 on admission to 11.4 4/14. Continues with hematuria, but denies current hematochezia. Suspect combination of blood loss and hypopoliferation given RPI 0.29, likely anemia of inflammation/acute illness given ferritin 1.010. Vitamin B12 >2000, Folate 11. Iron 151, unable to calculate TIBC. Noted to have persistently low MCV in low 70. Hemoglobin electrophoresis ordered.    #Vitamin D deficiency #HyperPTH 25-OH Vitamin D 6. No e/o hypocalcemia. Phos slightly elevated on admission, but subsequently downtrending, likely iso renal dysfunction. Treated with ergocalciferol 50,000 U weekly x12 weeks   #Right mandible lesion Sclerotic changes of the right mandible near the condyle noted on CT scan. Surgeon recommends outpatient follow-up, although patient declined.    #Hematochezia #Hemorrhoids Patient with new bloody diarrhea 4/11. Some e/o hemorrhoids on exam. CBC stable. Treated with tucks pads, dibucaine ointment and hydrocortisone cream.   #Little Medical Follow-up Pt reports that he has not seen a doctor in ~3 years.Cholesterol 124l LDL 73, HDL 10. HgbA1c 5.2. Will join Dr's panel on discharge   #CHIP mutation  RHP with DNMT3A mutation at low VAF. Will follow in cancer precursor clinic
HISTORY: Asthma, Hypertension, Eosinophilia noted on past lab values

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Not too many adverse symptoms the day of and after vaccine... tired at times and sensitivity to light but continued to eat and helped w energy.   Also, warm left side of neck and slight red rash.  Not expecting to have leg pain in my calf 6 days later then moved to quad muscle and entire left leg felt achy.  CDC at this point said to check out any leg pain.  Pain was not severe but bothersome... had STAT ultra sound at ER on day 7, turned out negative for blood clots.  Returned to my physicians office day 8... still not feeling right with more of a rash on left side of neck and warm to the touch. Tired and slightly light headed and slight pain in left upper chest.  Digestion not the best starting day 5 thru 10.  Blood test returned normal for platelet levels but low eosinophils... either allergies or body is fighting the vaccine and creating antibodies (most likely).  No known allergies besides maybe skin reaction to Timothy Bluegrass.  Moderate headache day 9 and 10 which made me more fatigued (pain on both sides of head above ears and temples)... normally I do not get headaches.  Also, loss of appetite or feeling slight nauseous on day 8, 9, and 10 after the vaccine.   Now on day 11 and 12.. feeling better but still not quite right.  Lightheaded and feeling fullness in head but more energy than day 9 and 10 by far.  Never heard of people having symptoms after day 1 or 2 of the vaccine, so obviously I think this should be more documented for patients especially after blood clotting as a possibility 6 days after the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Negative STAT ultrasound at ER, normal platelet levels, yet low eosinophils
HISTORY: Under active Thyroid but controlled w NP Thyroid meds

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She had the vaccine, when  she woke up the next day her arm was really sore and kept bending it, and thought that she was going to be okay.  Almost a week later it was swollen, parallel to it and big, beat red, and hot to touch.  Over the next few days she was getting more and more tired, but the arm started getting stiffer.  It kept getting  more and more read and spreading to the elbow and wrist.  When she got up over the weekend and kept putting it off thinking that it would go away and decided to touch it out.  Then it started getting numb going into her fingers.  On the following Saturday she could not move her arm up due to stiffness.  She had some heart flutters, was not feeling right and decided she needed to see her doctor.   She saw a NP and then she went to see her cardiologist the same day.  He did an EKG and told her that she was fine.  That is the provider that told her that whoever gave her the shot hit a blood vessel that caused all of her symptoms.  The swelling was starting to go down and did some tests for blood testing, which she states was all negative.   She went to an eye doctor who is now sending her to a neurologist.    She has now recovered from it completely now.
OTHER_MEDS: Atorvastatin, Levothyroxine, Losartan/HCTZ, Lysine, multivitamin, baby aspirin., Glycinamide.
HISTORY: Thyroid disease, high cholesterol, bridge in her heart.

She had the Johnson and Johnson vaccine about 6 days ago and about 6 hours later she woke up with a tingling and swollen lip, constricted breathing, and dizziness. She wanted to avoid the hospital, so she took benadryl 75 mg and it slowly resolved her symptoms. These symptoms have not returned since. She was finally able to fall asleep that night and then slept all day the next day. The following day she woke up and experienced extreme pain in her lower back and tailbone. She saw her chiropractor twice this past week, which helped to resolve her low back pain. Per patient her chiropractor noted that her back seemed very inflamed. However, she is still having extreme pain with her tailbone and is unable to sit, stand, bend or work for more than 20 minutes without extreme pain. The only thing that seems to improve her pain is laying on her back with several pillows tucked behind and all around her. However, she is only able to stay in this position for a period of time before her body becomes stiff from immobility. She has been taking ibuprofen 600 mg TID, flexeril PRN, icing and applying moist heat to her back, but none of these measures seem to improve her pain. Lastly she has noticed that when she sits/stands for too long, her buttocks start to spasm. Denies fever, chills, n/v, numbness, tingling, incontinence or loss of bowel/bladder function."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe throat tightening, itching body, mild hives on hands. I have to take Benadryl every 4 hours to keep these side effects tolerable. I emailed my doctor to see how long this would last or if there is anything I need to be doing. They called me and told me to come in right away. I was unable to see my doctor but was seen by another doctor. She said I was definitely having an allergic reaction after scratching my skin, looking in my nose, ears, and mouth.  She asked if I had changed anything like soaps or laundry detergent recently, which I told her I did not. I said the only thing out of the ordinary that I have done in the past YEAR has been getting the COVID vaccine. She then told me it was probably just seasonal allergies.. which I have never had before. She wrote on my after care summary that I could use OTC eye drops for my eye symptoms (and I don?t have ANY eye symptoms), she also wrote that I could use Flonase for my nose symptoms (which I don?t have any nose symptoms), and to buy Zyrtec for keeping the seasonal allergies at bay. She didn?t even consider the vaccine to be an issue. I also didn?t even know throat tightness could be a vaccine side effect until I looked it up. I don?t know why I was brushed off and told seasonal allergies when my side effects don?t line up with that. I don?t think it was a coincidence I received the vaccine and started to have ?seasonal allergies?. I asked if I should be getting an allergy test to see what ?seasonal? things I?m having this reaction to and she said that doesn?t matter, just to keep treating the symptoms.  So no tests were given.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient experienced shortness of breath and anxiety post vaccination, recovered and released.

The expected soreness in my arm developed throughout the afternoon of the morning (Friday) I had the shot along with a fever. I had fever and chills all night - my teeth chattered all night. The fever continued throughout Saturday and my nose was congested. My chest felt tight. Of most concern my neck was so stiff Saturday and Sunday that I could not move it or turn it in the slightest. The pain radiated down through the shoulders but no further. The overwhelming fatigue I had felt when I had Covid in late March-early April was back. I could not stand long without having to sit down and walking around made me feel breathless. I stayed in bed all weekend. The fever broke Sunday night and by Monday morning I could move my neck,  but it was very tender and I did not have my normal range of motion. My congestion turned into a runny nose on Monday which cleared on Tuesday. By Tuesday my energy level was close to normal and I had full range of neck motion, although still tender. I never had a headache at any point over those four days.

The same day, I was exhausted. It lasted 2 days. After that, on the 2nd or 3rd day after my shot, my right calf began to hurt. I knew it was connected to the vaccine, but I figured it would go away. Once the information came out about blood clots and my calf still hurt and didn't get better, I decided to go and get it checked out.

Patient came in forher first dose of the Moderan vaccine.  Patient is an overnight associate.  We processed her paperwork, I asked her if she felt ok (answered the questions she had fiklled out) and then I proceeded to have her sit in the booth.  When I went into the booth, I explained to her when her second dose was and to bring back her vaccine card.  She stated she did not really want to get the shot, but was being pressured by her mom.  I asked her if she was sure she wanted the shot, and she said yes because her dad has a heart condition.  I then proceeded to administer the shot at 8:12 am.  She did very well with the shot- no bleeding in the bandaid. I asked her to sit for about 10 minutes.  I proceeded to walk back into the pharmacy, and I dispoded of the gloves.  I then walked over to my computer, then I heard the loud thump at 8:14 am.  I immedietly ran out to the booth and she had fallen over.  We called a code white and called 911.  Pt was awake, hit her head and mouth. I asked her if she had eaten and she said she could not remember,  She said the shot was fine and she was on her phone and that is all she remembers.  I rubber her back and chatted with her until the fire department arrived.  She was able to call her cousin from her phone, but I did not move her until the fire department came.  EMS came and she went with them. EMS stated that she had not slept in 24 hours and  that could be the cause.  The time from the shot to the thump was no more than 1 minute.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had parked in the COVID vaccine waiting area, and was observed to fall forward onto his steering wheel within a few minutes of parking by 2 other participants waiting in the car next to him. One of them immediately notified one of the parking lot volunteers who came and got me within 1 minute of this observation. 2 students and I came quickly to the open drivers side door and began talking to assess the situation. Mr. Bannister appeared pale, mildly diaphoretic (sweating) and slightly confused as to the passage of time, but was able to state and spell his name and talk coherently about his circumstances. He stated that he was not allergic to anything that he knew about, and that he had no prior history of similar reactions to vaccines or medicines although he had not taken any shots in several years. He noted that he had not eaten anything since breakfast (now mid-afternoon). He described himself as initially feeling weak, faint, and nauseated with his vaccinated arm feeling heavy and numb. He also reported that he had a sensation of blurriness before passing out, but denied any spinning sensation, visual loss or ringing in the ears. There were no obviously visible abrasions or bleeding on his face or forehead. The nursing students brought a chair, and we elevated his legs and gave him some water to drink during the time we were monitoring his vital signs. He refused a cupcake because of the nausea, but as time progressed he gained facial color and was more comfortable in conversing. His hands had equal muscle grip and strength, visible fingernail beds were pink and his capillary refill was less than 3 seconds. Towards the end of our monitoring, he did accept some nuts and M & Ms to eat. A University Safety Medical Report was completed by the appropriate safety personnel. He was fully AAO x 3 at the end of our monitoring, and stated that if he felt better he would drive to his apartment (less than 5 minutes away) but would wait for his girlfriend to get out of class if he did not feel fully capable of driving. We encouraged him to eat something light when he got home, to use cool water/warm water soaks at his shot site, exercise his arm, and to take an NSAID for pain relief the next day. We recommended that he eat something light before his second shot (which had already been scheduled), that he bring someone with him the next time, and as a precaution to wait 30 minutes following the second shot. He left at 3: 15 pm driving his car without any apparent difficulties. An online report was completed for the incident 04/20/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 81-year-old woman who last Tuesday received her second vaccination shot in her left arm.  Several hours after the procedure she developed pain and discomfort in her left arm.  The left arm discomfort gradually increased over the past 3 to 4 days and she began to experience symptoms of claudication in her left forearm and hand.  She had a difficult time performing her daily tasks.  The pain significantly worsened today to the point that she had constant pain in her hand and developed numbness in her fingers.  She presented to the urgent care clinic and was subsequently transferred to the emergency room where CT angiogram demonstrates thrombus in her left brachial artery.  She denies a history of heart palpitations.  She has no history of hypercoagulable state.  She has no history of blood clots or easy bleeding.  She has no history of infection and denies fevers chills or night sweats.  She has no significant history of peripheral vascular disease and can walk over a mile without difficulty.  She denies symptoms of transient ischemic attacks.  Left brachial ulnar and radial artery thrombectomy due to inflammation of the brachial artery and thrombus in the brachial artery extending into the origin of the radial and ulnar arteries done on 3/22/2021. Discharged on aspirin 81 mg daily and Lovenox. Has transitioned to Eliquis now. Complication of left arm wound dehiscence. Debrided by wound clinic on 4/9/2021. Taken for washout/wound closure on 4/13/2021. Continues to f/u in our clinic.

I advised her to come in for evaluation if rash or  swelling became worse, asymmetric, or if new symptoms begin.

In the morning of April 17, the soreness/tingling remained in the left arm. I took one ibuprofen and the feeling went away. In the evening of April 17, I had one glass of red wine and the soreness/numb/tingling feeling returned to my left arm. I took one ibuprofen and the feeling went away. I have not had any alcohol since, and have not had any soreness/numb/tingling in my left arm since. I have not experienced this feeling in my arm at any other time, including after annual flu shots. I have had some mild and transient tinnitus in the past (nothing like what happened after the vaccine), but have had very few problems over the last couple years. It usually happened when I slept wrong (neck issue) and then went away not long after getting out of bed.  It is now exactly two weeks after the first dose and the tinnitus has decreased but is still present. I have not gone to my doctor as they report not knowing much about the connection between the vaccine and tinnitus. I have tried a few things suggested on-line with indeterminant results. It does appear to be lessening with time and hopefully that progress will continue. I am concerned about getting the second dose since the side-effects are reported to be worse with the second dose of all the Covid-19 vaccines. I don't want to be left with a permanent problem especially one that is really intrusive and hard to manage.

Approximately 3 to 5 minutes after immunization, patient was observed  in a waiting room chair unconscious, unresponsive and not breathing (respiration was not immediately observable or recognizable).  Patient was carefully and quickly placed in a supine position on the floor.  Pulse was present but the patient was completely unresponsive.  Respiration was not observed.  EMS was immediately notified.  Pharmacist and staff prepared for resuscitation and utilization of Epinephrine if needed.  Patients face was flushed, arms became flushed and the patients skin became moist.  After approximately  45 seconds in the supine position the patients eyes opened and he became responsive to auditory communication.  Respiration became reestablished.  BP was recorded at 130/91 with a pulse of 91 BPM.  EMS arrived on scene and provided further evaluation.  After an additional 5-10 minutes, patient was completely conscious and coherent.  Patient indicated that he had a similar experience in a grocery store over 1 year ago that was unrelated to immunization and was attributed to dehydration.  Patient refused additional medical care or transport to ED.  Patient was released to a friend who drove him home.  Patient was observed 1 day later picking up his car from the pharmacy and has recovered.  Patient was advised to seek additional medical evaluation to assess the root cause of this event.

12 hours after my dose (on Saturday), going to bed at 10:30 and tired, I began to feel a low-grade temperature set in, and I woke up 2 hours later during the night and was having soreness in my lower back as the most pronounced.  I had trouble sleeping through most of the night and got up twice to urinate.  I could not get comfortable enough to fall asleep - was not necessarily feeling pain, just soreness.  During the day Sunday, I tried to rest having lost sleep, and it was mainly my lower back (back strap muscles) which were experiencing soreness.  Sunday evening, I went to bed around 9:30, and I woke up around midnight having a sore neck.  It felt like I was not necessarily sore in the muscles, but I could feel my heart rate increase and my blood pumping through my neck to my brain.  I could not get comfortable at all and lost sleep.  During the day Monday, I tried to rest it off, and there was no position I could rest where I was not in pain in my neck.  It almost felt like I had some form of encephylitis.  I went to bed around 8:30 PM, exhausted.  Woke up around midnight again, and I could not get back to sleep until 4 AM.  I found a position where my head turned and my shoulder extended away was not painful.  I woke up having felt like I had strained that muscle however.
ALLERGIES: Mild to Moderate asthma (I will begin an asthma attack if I cough or sneeze openly, not holding it in).  Seasonal allergies to mold, some tree pollen, and definitely ragweed

Parent and patient both stated that was incorrect and the real DOB is 9/29/2004. We explained to them that they should call the insurance and get it fixed because if we try to run it through with that DOB it gives us a stop because you have to be 16 to get the vaccine.  Parent stated that they would just pay for it and call insurance later to get it fixed. So we verified that DOB was 9/29/2004 and he was in fact 16 they both stated yes, so we got parent's ID and patient's ID (patient only had school ID with no verifiable DOB on it) and ran it though under no ins and gave the vaccine.   4/19/21 -- Email stating that we incorrectly gave dose to 15 year old. I explained the situation and they stated that the DOB they have cannot be incorrect because it is from the state vital records.   4/20/21 -- I called parent he had no recollection of our conversation and stated that the DOB is 9/29/2005, so he is in fact only 15 years old. I explained to him that patient should not have been given the vaccine and that we won't be able to give the 2nd dose until he is 16 years old. Put in incident report and VAERS report

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was 4 weeks pregnant (with a PGS normal embryo) at the time of vaccination. In addition to the usual IVF transfer related medications (estradiol & progesterone), I was taking prednisone to suppress my immune system (based on a high ANA value). The baby stopped growing at 6 1/2 weeks, which would be shortly after the first vaccine reached its maximum effect. While I don't believe that the vaccine directly harmed the fetus, I do believe that by stimulating my immune system, it overrode the prednisone I was taking to suppress my immune system. In all the research I did prior to vaccination, I never saw this mentioned. It would help the many women taking prednisone for an auto-immune issue during pregnancy if you advised them to wait until after the first trimester, when auto-immune issues have less impact on the fetus.
LAB_DATA: A D&C is scheduled for this Friday and the intent is to test the fetus to confirm it was chromosomally normal (as the PGS test said). There are additional tests scheduled for 2 weeks later to see if anything else could have contributed, but it is likely to confirm the role that auto-immune plays in my pregnancies.  I was tested & found negative for any recent Parvo infection.  This is the first pregnancy loss since I started taking prednisone for pregnancy.
OTHER_MEDS: Prednisone, 20 mg daily, Folic Acid supplement, Prenatal Vitamin, Estradiol, Progesterone 1 mg daily.

Patient came in for her first dose of Moderna vaccine today.   I was called by MA to see Patient as Patient was having symptom(s) 15 minutes after the vaccine was given.     I saw Patient at 0935.  Patient stated that she feels pressure in her anterior throat, that it was hard for her to swallow saliva, and that her tongue felt big.     I performed physical examination: Cardiovascular:  RRR S1 S2 Pulmonary:  Lungs clear to auscultation Mouth/Throat:  Posterior pharynx doesn't look swollen, tongue doesn't look swollen  MA and myself continued to monitor Patient.     I asked Patient to call her mother who Patient stated was waiting downstairs.     I asked MA to obtain vitals: BP:  128/79 HR:  102 bpm   I explained to Patient and mother that I think Patient should be given the Epi-pen in order to prevent any of the symptom(s) from worsening.   Patient and mother agreed to have the Epi-pen administered.     At 0950, Patient stated that her tongue doesn't feel big anymore, but that she still feels pressure in her anterior throat.  Patient asked for water, she was given a water bottle by MA.  After drinking water, Patient stated it was hard to swallow the water.     At 0955, I administered the Epi-pen in Patient's right thigh.  Patient felt okay with the administration of the Epi-pen.   I asked  MA to observe Patient for 15 minutes, Mom was in the room with the Patient as well.   At 1015, I went in to see Patient, and per MA and Patient, Patient was feeling much better.  Patient stated that her symptom(s) had resolved, she was not feeling pressure in her anterior throat any longer, she was able to drink water normally, and she didn't feel that her tongue felt big any longer.     I performed repeat physical examination: Cardiovascular:  RRR S1 S2 Pulmonary:  Lungs clear to auscultation Mouth/Throat:  Posterior pharynx didn't look swollen, tongue didn't look swollen   I asked  MA to obtain repeat vitals: BP:  116/73 HR 94 bpm   I have advised Patient to talk to her PCP about whether she should get the second dose of Moderna, or perhaps get another vaccine such as Pfizer in place of the second dose of Moderna.     I have let Patient know that I will CC her chart to her PCP and will try to get a Telemedicine visit with the doctor for Patient during the next week.     I have let Patient know that I will e-prescribe Epi-pen for her.     I have advised Patient and Mom that if symptom(s) worsen or if new symptom(s) start (such as chest pain, SOB, hives, throat/mouth/face/tongue swelling or any other concerning symptoms) to take Patient to the ED.    Mom and Patient understood and agreed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was ordered to receive Menveo (meningococcal vaccine ACYW), which is a lyophylized powder (containing serogroup A) and a diluent (containing serogroups CYW). The pharmacy erroneously dispensed the lyophylized powder component of Menveo (serogroup A only) and a vial of Menactra (serogroups ACYW). The RN reconstituted the Menveo vial with Menactra and administered this to patient before error was noted.  Patient has not reported any ADRs in past 24 hours. Reviewed with clinic and will not re-administer dose as patient did receive full vaccination but as Manactra rather than Menveo.  The pharmacy does store Menactra and Menveo separate from one another (in different refrigerators in different sections of the pharmacy) but it is suspected that a staff member erroneously returned a dose of Menactra to the Menveo storage location and this wasn't caught during filling. The pharmacist who checked the dose thought the "diluent" vial looked odd, but the Menveo vial said  to reconstituted with the "MenCYW-135 conjugate component" and the Menveo vial said it contained meningicoccal ACY,W and so the pharmacist thought it was correct.

I got into the shower (dumb idea) and the spinning was no longer occurring, but I still felt off-balance and got a bit nauseous. I did some vertigo relief maneuvers and they've helped, but I can tell I'm not 100% back to normal as of writing (11:54am). I would say I'm 90% back to normal. TTE obtained, without evidence of right heart strain. Patient is a 72 y.o. female who presents to the office today stating "I do not feel so good".   She mentions noting blurry vision over the past 1 week right eye only with decreased vision.  Denies any eye pain.  Thinks her vision is worse outside in the sun.   In addition, today she states she was up moving around getting ready for today's appointment when all of a sudden she felt a brief slight low light shock pointing to left anterior chest wall.  Denies any chest pain or pressure but reports noting her heart rate was elevated up to 150.  She states her O2 sat at home was 97% on room air.  She checked her blood pressure which was not abnormal but cannot recall the number.   She was recently diagnosed with a PE for which she was hospitalized, see previous note.  She is concerned as she feels perhaps her Covid vaccine initially received on 3/4/2021 could have caused her blood clot.  Her second dose was received on 3/31/2021 and has since not been feeling well EKG in the office with new onset A. fib relation noted, rapid ventricular rate with a pulse of 152 bpm.  911 was called and patient transferred to the ER for further evaluation and recommendations.  Patient currently on Eliquis for PE  Patient, with a past medical history of essential hypertension, mixed hyperlipidemia and grade 1 diastolic dysfunction, as well as acute bilateral pulmonary emboli 3/2021 diagnosed a few days after her first dose of the Pfizer Covid vaccination, now anticoagulated on Eliquis who presented to KMC emergency room on 4/14/2021 from her primary care provider's office after being found in newly diagnosed atrial fibrillation with RVR, rate in the 150s.  Of note, patient had received her second dose of the Pfizer Covid vaccine on 4/10/2021.  She had scheduled this primary care provider appointment due to waxing and waning blurred vision of her right eye, with associated right-sided headache that had been ongoing over the last week.  Patient reports that on the day of arrival she had not felt well, felt slightly weak and fatigued, but denied shortness of breath, chest pain or heart palpitations.  Per ER notes, patient was instructed on vagal maneuvers while she was in the ambulance, and had converted to sinus rhythm by the time of her arrival to the emergency room.  Per review of her telemetry on the day of discharge, patient did have one short episode of PAF on 4/15/2021, spontaneously converting to sinus rhythm, as well was intermittent PACs.  Her home lisinopril was changed to Coreg, without further episodes of RVR and with good blood pressure control.   In regards to her headache, patient underwent an MRI of the brain, which was negative for acute findings; she had no temporal tenderness, and ESR was within normal limits.  She did improve symptomatically with administration of Tylenol and Zofran for her corresponding nausea/vomiting.  On the day of discharge, patient was feeling much better, and stable for discharge.  An appointment with doctor of ophthalmology was offered to patient for 4/16/2021, however due to transportation issues, this was rescheduled for 4/20/2021.  She was instructed on changes in her medication, as well as encouraged to schedule an appointment with her established cardiologist.  All questions and concerns were addressed.
OTHER_MEDS: Tylenol, Eliquis, Coreg, Vitamin D, Prozac, Flonase, Zofran, Crestor
HISTORY: Hypertension, Chronic diastolic congestive heart failure, left ventriculat hypertrophy, morbid obesity, vitamin D deficiency, predabetes, pure hypercholesterolemia

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Four days after receiving my first dose, I developed hives covering my chest. These particular hives disappeared within a few hours, but following that first outbreak I continued to have hives every day for 10 days. The hives would occur at different times on all parts of my body, including  my face and the palms of my hands and the bottoms of my feet. The hives were often itchy. There seemed to be a contact component, in that pressure on my skin would cause the hives to occur in a given spot, though contact may not have been the reason for all of the hives. At times, my entire torso would be covered, and when I woke up in the morning, my legs were often impacted. To treat the hives, I took Benadryl at night, which is often when the hives were worst, though I would still wake up with hives in the morning. It is difficult to say if the Benadryl was effective. On April 19th, I woke up with hives on my legs, but these disappeared after a few hours, per usual. I didn't develop any more hives throughout the day or evening, and as April 20th have not developed any more hives. Over the course of the 10 days, I considered whether external allergens may have been the cause of the hives, but numerous measures taken to alleviate the situation did not result in any change. (And the pollen on the trees outside eventually dissipated though the hives did not.) During this time, I also experienced some mild chest pain and coughing. I had a Covid-19 test on April 14th that returned a negative result on  April 16th.
LAB_DATA: I did not undergo any medical or lab testing, but on April 19th I did speak with a dermatologist who looked at pictures of my hives. She confirmed that they were, in fact, hives and offered that they may be the result of a reaction to the Covid vaccine. She recommended an antihistamine treatment regimen, but my hives did not return so I didn't pursue the treatment.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am submitting this report because of symptom onset relative to vaccination date, and because I have not experienced this cluster of symptoms before.  My wife and I received the same lot number of the J&J vaccine on Saturday, March 13. We both had slight fatigue that evening and into the following day and she has had no further symptoms.  On Tuesday, March 16, I had a mild ache around injection site with no further symptoms until Saturday, March 27 when I experienced a brief episode of lightheadedness. (CONTINUED BELOW) Sunday March 28 another episode of lightheadedness in the evening. Sent in report from remote pacemaker monitor which showed no abnormalities.  March 29 through April 2: Continued lightheaded episodes (brief lasting no more than a few seconds) plus evening chills and headache with temperatures in 99.4 - 99.8 range.  April 1: I was seen in cardiology clinic where my pacemaker was thoroughly interrogated with no evidence of arrythmias or technical issues.  April 2: Covid PCR test ordered by PCP (Dr.) for both myself and wife. This was done on the following day with both of us testing negative.  April 5: Seen by PCP and the probability of this being a late onset vaccine reaction was suggested. CBC (WNL) and Lyme antibody (neg) drawn.  April 8: Upon awaking in the morning, brief episode of dizziness/vertigo along with markedly increased tingling in both feet. I also began to experience a skin sensation (resembling application of eucalyptus or peppermint oils) on torso and legs, typically on awakening from sleep or after meals. Seen again by PCP. Findings on exam were absence of vibratory sense in both feet and absent Achilles reflexes bilaterally. Referral to neurology discussed.   April 12: Seen and examined again in PCP's office. Labs drawn: CBC w/dif;   Sed Rate;   Complete Metabolic Panel;   TSH;   Free T3;   B12. All within normal limits except for random glucose of 141mg/dl. Plan for referral to neurology.  April 14: Late evening my blood pressure spiked to 198/106 which I was able to bring down to normal with extra meds. Subsequent BP checks have been ok.  The symptoms described above (April 8) continued on a daily basis until Tuesday April 13, on which day I was pretty much asymptomatic. However, they have continued episodically, though with decreasing frequency and intensity. And finally, I don't recall the exact dates but during the week  following April 8 I experienced two (non-consecutive) episodes of night sweats and one late evening hot flash with sweating lasting about a minute or so.
LAB_DATA: 04/05/21: CBC (WNL);   Lyme Antibody w/Reflex (Negative) 04/12/21: CBC w/diff;   CMP;   Sed Rate;   B12;   TSH;   Free T4;   (all WNL except glucose of 141mg/dl)
OTHER_MEDS: Atenolol;   Losartan;   Atorvastatin;   Low-dose Aspirin; Famotidine; Tadalafil; Paroxetine; Low-Dose Naltrexone (4.5mg); Multivitamin; Sublingual B12/B6/Folate; Vit C; Vit D; Meriva 500-SF (Curcumin Phytosome); OncoPlex (Glucoraphanin)
HISTORY: Type-2 Diabetes Mellitus;   Cardiac Pacemaker;   Hypertension;  BPH; Osteoarthritis;   GERD;   Neuropathy Both Feet; Posner-Schlossman Syndrome (aka Glaucomatocyclitic Crisis); Bilateral Cataracts; ADHD & Anxiety Disorder

Within 1 or 2 minutes after getting the vaccine I started to feel like the left side of my face was becoming flushed. For the rest of the day, the left side of my face felt very different from the right-side.  There was some pain around the temple.  The next day, and even through today, 5 days later, the problem has been mainly around my eye.  My eye often feels irritation when I blink and there is some muscular quivering of my lower eyelid. After speaking to my brother who is a radiologist he decided that it was unlikely to be an allergic reaction, and because the feeling of my face on the left side was reminiscent of the feeling I had a year ago when I had shingles around my left eye, he thought the reaction could very well be related to shingles.  In other words, there was a activation of a response that resembled my shingles episode.  This was bolstered by my speaking with my neighbor who also had the pfizer vaccine who said she had a very similar reaction affecting her face that lasted several days, and she,years before, had shingles on her face (as well as the shingles vaccine).

Patient received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 1, lot #EW0171, expiration date 8/2021) in his left deltoid at 1437. The client was observed to fall out of his chair in the observation area, fall to the ground, and hit his head. The client made no attempt to protect his head or break his fall. RN, PHN, RN, and RN responded at 1438. PHN called EMS at that time as well. The client was observed to jerk his arms twice. The client was unconscious for approximately 90 seconds, and was turned on his side at this time. When the client regained consciousness, he was alert and oriented, complained of no pain in his head or any dizziness or lightheadedness. No difficulty breathing. Pupils were equal and reactive to light. At 1439, the vital signs obtained were: blood pressure 130/90, heart rate 57, O2 98, respiratory rate 26. The client denied any history of seizures, epilepsy, or any other medical history. The client stated he has no allergies and that he takes no medications. Upon examination, there were no cuts observable on the client's head. The client denied any feelings of dizziness before his loss of consciousness but stated he did not eat any breakfast or lunch that day. At 1443, the repeat vitals were as follows: 128/94 blood pressure, heart rate 60, respiratory rate 22, temperature 98. A manual pulse was 88 and thready. At 1447, EMR responded to the scene and assumed care of the client. Client transported to hospital.

Pt. had (what we think) a small seizure on Thursday, March 18th and then again on Saturday, March 20th.  On Sunday, March 21st, 911 had to be called as his seizure did not end.  He had a grand male.  He was seizing for several hours.  At the time this was all occurring he has been on anti seizure meds for a few years Divalproex 1000 mg am and 1000 mgs pm daily).  He passed 1 week later, March 28 at approx 6:45pm at the Clinic.  I am unable to get any information  on his medical report for that week.  Statement from his Nurologists is on second page. Additional information for Item 18:   Statement:  47 year old gentleman who passed away on March 28 from aspiration pneumonia secondary to status epilepticus and on a history of multiple sclerosis / additional leukoencephalopathy of unknown etiology (both treated with rituximab), prior seizures (on valproic acid) and pulmonary embolism (on apixaban). The key reason for reaching out is in light of the announcement about the side effects of the Johnson & Johnson vaccine specifically cerebral venous sinus thrombosis. While he had a known history of seizures, he had no clear trigger for these seizures; including that his valproic acid level was therapeutic (83.0 mcg/mL) at time of presentation. He had, however, received the Johnson & Johnson vaccine on March 12 before having what in hindsight appeared to be repeated seizures between March 18-21; he had a more significant one on March 21 that hospitalized him. This time frame appears consistent with the reported cases of central venous sinus thrombosis associated with the Johnson & Johnson vaccine. Equally, he was taking apixaban at that point in time and his PLT (173) / INR (1.1) / PTT (36.6) at time of presentation were all normal and stable. He did have an elevated ProBNP (552.0) at presentation; nasopharyngeal swab was negative for COVID / Influenza A/B / RSV and non-contrast head CT did not show any clear new abnormalities. His only D-dimer was obtained on March 23 and was 226. He did not have a CT angiogram or venogram.   Overall the link between the vaccine and pt. seizures is not definite. At the same time, the similarity with the reported cases has led to me wanting to report it in case of the possible link. If you require further information then please don't hesitate to email me Pt. med list at the time of this incident  Modifinil - 100 mg/1per day/AM Sertraline - 100 mg/1per day/AM Vitamin D3 - 50 mg/1per day/AM Divalproex - 500 mg/2per day/AM Eliquis - 5 mg/1per day/AM Furoseminde - 20 mg/1per day/AM Metroprolol - 100 mg/1per day/AM Lisinopril - 10 mg/1per day/AM  Divalproex - 500 mg/2per day/PM Eliquis - 5 mg/1per day/PM Metroprolol - 100 mg/1per day/PM Melatonin - 5 mg/1per day/PM Quetiapine - 50 mg/3per day/PM
LAB_DATA: unable to get medical records from hospital

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient vaccinated around 9:57 AM. In observation and felt it was "hard to swallow". RN walked patient to the bed and took vital signs. DOC of the day called to assess the patient.
