Patient given water which visibly looked difficult to swallow. 50 mg IM Benadryl given to patient. Will continue to monitor.  After giving Benadryl, patient reported improvement in symptoms. About 10 minutes later, patient stated symptoms were coming back and were worse with posterior tongue swelling and throat constriction. 0.3 mg EPI pen administered to patient. EMS transport recommended to patient when EPI was given. Patient denied transport at that time. Patient instructed and educated on the risks of denying EMS transport. After ten minutes post EPI pen, patient and provider both agreed it necessary to call 911 because patient reported no significant improvement after EPI pen. 911 called at 1041 and arrived on scene at 1055. Patient taken to hospital. Patient awake and alert speaking in full sentences at the time of transport.

I received the Pfizer dose 1 vaccine from Dr. at clinic around 10:51AM on 04/09/2021 and was told to wait in my car, by myself, for 15 minutes after receiving the vaccine before driving home. Received email at 1:29 PM on 04/09/2021 that stated, " Hello there, We apologize for the inconvenience, but due to shortage and viability of the vaccines we would have to shutdown the clinic at the moment. We are currently in communication with the state government and will we send out an update as soon as we can. Once again, we apologize for the inconveniences this may cause. "I received an email at 10:19 PM and 10:22PM on 04/09/2021 that stated, " Hello, ? Department of Health and Environment has paused administration of COVID-19 vaccines at Clinic as a result of irregularities in vaccine storage and handling.  is working to determine whether the provider has records to show that storage protocols have been consistently adhered to, or if this was an isolated incident. Pending the results of this investigation, all COVID-vaccine Clinic are canceled. You will be contacted to reschedule your appointment at another time. For more information, please see this press release." I received an at 8:28 PM on 04/13/2021 that stated, " Hello, We wanted to provide you with the latest information on the  COVID-19 vaccination site. As you know, the Department of Health and Environment paused administration of all COVID-19 vaccines at as a result of potential irregularities in vaccine storage and handling. Through an investigation, we identified substandard vaccine storage and handling, vaccine preparation, mass clinic operations and poor recordkeeping practices. We want to reassure you that we do not believe anyone vaccinated at the  Clinic should be worried about their safety. Through our review, it has been determined that all patients who received a single COVID-19 vaccine at vaccination clinic should be offered revaccination. If you received one dose of Pfizer vaccine at vaccination clinic, that dose is considered invalid and you should receive two additional doses of Pfizer vaccine according to the time frames below: Additional dose of Pfizer 21 days after your initial invalid Pfizer dose was received at clinic, and Final dose of Pfizer 21 days later (e.g., 21 days after your repeated valid dose). If you received one dose of Moderna vaccine at a vaccination clinic, that dose is considered invalid and you should receive two additional doses of Moderna vaccine according to the time frames below: Additional dose of Moderna 28 days after your initial invalid Moderna dose was received at clinic, and Final dose of Moderna 28 days later (e.g., 28 days after your repeated valid dose) If you do not know which vaccine you received at a vaccination clinic, you should receive two additional doses of either Moderna or Pfizer vaccine according to the time frames below: Additional dose of Moderna or Pfizer 28 days after your initial invalid mRNA dose was received at clinic, and Final dose of Moderna or Pfizer 28 days later (e.g., 28 days after your repeated valid dose). We invite you to schedule your appointments for vaccination at another enrolled COVID-19 vaccine provider. There are many sites in County and elsewhere. People needing assistance finding a vaccine site near them or scheduling an appointment can call our 24-hour hotline that is available to answer questions in multiple languages. I called Pfizer to understand their guidance on 4/20/2021 at 1:25PM to understand their guidance and research for patient who received non-viable vaccines and they were not able to provide me with any information. I also asked if they have research for individual who are receiving recommendations to receive three vaccinations and they were not able to provide any guidance or share any research findings to answer that question either.

I could only smell and taste metal STRONGLY and a ringing in my ears as well as a low grade metallic headache.  I also cried at every moment for NO REASON. It eventually tapered off and the redness/bruising disappeared over the next 48 hours. There was no pain, no warning - just a mouth full of blood. The tonsil that ruptured was on the same side as where I received the injection and I had swollen lymph nodes under my arm on that same side until Sunday 4/18. I can't help but think it was related to the vaccine as I had no other cold/hay fever/allergy symptoms of any kind to explain a bleeding tonsil.

Fatigue set in about 11 hours after I was given the shot on Sunday, but it was bedtime so I didn't think much of it. At 1:15 am, I woke to violent shaking all over, and all-over achiness but no fever. I took one 500 mg Tylenol, and slept fitfully, I felt like I was aware that I was extremely uncomfortable, and I was either too cold or too hot. My temperature fluctuated from normal to about 100.8, on and off all the next day. It was an extreme effort and it was difficult to even shift my body position in bed, and my arm that was vaccinated could barely move and it hurt tremendously. My head ached, and my lower back ached the most, aside from my arm. I slept nearly all day yesterday (Monday), and I was very weak, with hardly any appetite. It took all effort to get out of bed to use the bathroom. I took a Tylenol 500 mg pill every 5-6 hours and those first couple hours felt the most pain relief. I counted down the time to get past 5 hours to take another one. Around 7 pm, after sleeping all day, I got out of bed to sit upright on the couch to relieve my back pain, and that helped. Symptoms started easing up later last night. I slept more than 9 hours again and today am feeling weak but no body aches or headache, only my arm is sore but not as bad as it was yesterday. I am less fatigued today but moving slowly, and my appetite is slowly returning. I have avoided taking more Tylenol since bedtime last night and feel like the worst is behind me. I hope.
HISTORY: Crohn's Disease, stage 3 kidney disease (chronic kidney stones), small bowel syndrome

a 27 y.o. female with a history of Covid infection December 26, 2020, positive covid test December 29, 2020. She had approximately 2 weeks of symptoms including generalized body ache and generalized weakness.  Fatigue and some headache.  Had some persistence of symptoms after that time.  Had some benefit from ibuprofen.   Was seen at emergency room on January 27, 2021 stating that she felt that all her symptoms of Covid had resolved except for some chest pain which awoke her on January 27.  She presented to the emergency room.  Had sinus tachycardia at 113 but otherwise unremarkable physical exam, laboratory studies with white blood count elevated 16,004-20, hemoglobin 13.7 g hematocrit 41.8%, MCV 87.1, RDW 12.7%, platelet count 329,000, segs 72.8%, lymphs 20.6%, monocytes 4%, eosinophils 1%, basophil 0.6%.  BUN 10.1, creatinine 0.8, AST 24, ALT elevated 56, alkaline phosphatase 68, total protein 7.6, total bilirubin 0.3, albumin 3.6, globulin by subtraction 4.0, troponin less than 0.02, D-dimer quantitative 0.22, urine pregnancy test normal.  Chest x-ray normal.  Chest pain appears to be musculoskeletal and was reproduced by palpation of her chest wall.  No evidence of deep venous thrombosis or pulmonary embolism.  D-dimer was normal.  Heart rate returned to normal after some intravenous fluids.  Patient discharged on Zithromax 500 mg day 1 and then to 50 mg days 2 through 5.  Also continued on ibuprofen.   Received Johnson and Johnson vaccine April 5, 2021.  Over the next week patient started having increasing soreness.  Her joints hurt more than usual and her headache was worse.  She had a sensation that her legs were "numb and tingly" starting at her buttocks and extending down her leg.   Because of reported incidence of cerebral sinus thrombosis or cerebral vein thrombosis patient appropriately presented for screening in the emergency room and was sent for appropriate imaging.   April 16, 2021 CT scan of head with and without contrast no acute intracranial hemorrhage, no mass-effect or midline shift.  On contrast-enhanced images there appears to be a lobular nonocclusive filling defect in the far lateral right transverse sinus.  Lobular occlusive filling defect is also likely present in the mid to central right transverse sinus.  Short segment filling defect in the medial left transverse sinus.  Remainder of sinuses and internal cerebral veins are patent.  Focal lobular filling defect within the confluence of the right and transverse sinus most likely related to arachnoid granulation.  No edema hemorrhage of the cerebellum or cerebrum.  No other significant findings.   April 16, 2021 confirmatory MRI angiogram of head without contrast with no restricted diffusion to suggest acute or subacute infarct.  Contrast void in the middle to central right transverse sinus consistent with occlusive thrombus.  Nonocclusive thrombus in the far lateral right transverse thrombus.  Narrowing of the medial left transverse sinus without complete occlusion.   April 16, 2021 2345 hrs. inital hematology consultation.  D-dimer and fibrinogen levels have been requested stat and are still pending.  If fibrinogen level is low will replace with cryoprecipitate.  If D-dimer is elevated barely confirms diagnosis of possible vaccine related thrombosis.  The fact the patient is not thrombocytopenic at this time is encouraging, however despite the lack of thrombocytopenia she still has clearly documented symptomatic nonocclusive and occlusive thrombus in her cerebral sinus.   From UPtoDate.com Ad26.COV2.S (Janssen COVID-19 vaccine, also referred to as the Johnson & Johnson vaccine) ? On April 13, 2021, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommended pausing administration of AD26.COV2.S  to further investigate rare cases of cerebral venous sinus thrombosis and thrombocytopenia [33]. As of that date, six cases had been reported, all in females aged 18 to 48 years with onset 6 to 13 days after vaccination; during this period, 6.8 million doses were administered (with 1.5 million doses in females of that age range) [121-123]. Since some vaccine recipients have not been followed for longer than the time frame over which these symptoms develop, the incidence may change with additional follow-up. Initial symptoms included headache, backache, chills, and fatigue, and progressed to focal neurologic deficits. Intracerebral hemorrhage and thromboses at other sites were also seen in some patients. All of the five patients who were tested for the anti-PF4 HIT antibody tested positive. Another case, in a young male who was a vaccine recipient in one of the pre-emergency use authorization efficacy trials, had been previously reported. These cases appear similar to those reported following ChAdOx1 nCoV-19/AZD1222, another adenovirus-vector vaccine. Although rare, the observed number of events exceeded the expected rate among females <50 years old. Given the extreme rarity of these events, the FDA and CDC acknowledge that they recommended the pause out of an abundance of caution and to ensure awareness of these rare events.    ?Evaluation and management of possible thrombotic complications ? Recipients should be aware of the possible association and seek immediate care for signs and symptoms suggestive of thrombocytopenia (eg, new petechiae or bruising) or thrombotic complications (including shortness of breath, chest pain, lower extremity edema, persistent severe abdominal pain, unabating severe headache, severe backache, new focal neurologic symptoms, and seizures) [117]. In such cases, some experts suggest evaluation with complete blood count and differential (including the platelet count), quantitative D-dimer, HIT testing, and imaging of any suspected site of thrombosis [113,114,125]. Onset 4 to 20 days after vaccination, platelet count <150,000/microL, elevated D-dimer, and a positive anti-PF4 antibody (HIT antibody) suggest the diagnosis. Treatment with a non-heparin/non-warfarin anticoagulant (eg, argatroban or direct oral anticoagulant) and intravenous immune globulin has been suggested. The CDC recommends not using heparin in individuals with thromboses following receipt of Ad26.COV2.S unless HIT testing is negative [126]. (See "Cerebral venous thrombosis: Etiology, clinical features, and diagnosis" and "Clinical presentation and diagnosis of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia", section on 'Terminology and HIT variants' and "Management of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia", section on 'Role of IVIG'.)   As stated above all the 6 cases were "all in females aged 18 to 48 years with onset 6 to 13 days after vaccination" this would certainly fit the timeframe that we are seeing in this case.  Recommendations from national guidelines would be to start treatment with dexamethasone immediately while awaiting intravenous gammaglobulin.  To pursue intravenous gammaglobulin treatment at 1 g/kg over 1 to 2 days.  It is recommended to avoid heparin and instead use direct factor X inhibitor such as Eliquis, which this patient is already been started on.     There is unfortunately considerable risk that even though patient's symptoms appear mild at this time, that she may deteriorate in the very near future and I would recommend treating her aggressively at this time with dexamethasone and intravenous gammaglobulin while we are awaiting further testing.  Patient clearly has had unusual thrombosis, especially in a 27-year-old.     With the fact that she had headache dating back to January, it is impossible to determine the acute versus chronic nature of her venous sinus thrombosis. Covid infection does cause increase in coagulation as well.  However, given the small risk of tragic outcome with cerebral vein and sinus thrombosis in the setting of Covid vaccinations, we will proceed aggressively with treatment starting tonight with intravenous gammaglobulin and intravenous dexamethasone.     Will require rapid fasting glucoses to evaluate possible hyperglycemia from high-dose dexamethasone.  Will consider stopping dexamethasone at 48 hours.  Current recommendation for gammaglobulin would be single 1 g/kg or 500 mg/kg over 2 days.  No recommendations for treatment beyond this point.  Current recommendations for gammaglobulin dosing would recommend using an adjusted dose for patients with greater than 125% of their ideal body weight.  This patient at 122 kg on a 5 foot 2 inch frame does qualify for adjusted dose and her orders reflect that.   I appreciate the opportunity see this patient this evening and consultation requested by Dr.  We will follow patient in hospital.  Hopefully she will have gradual improvement and avoid any serious or tragic complications of her cerebral sinus thrombosis.     We will have pharmacy report possible adverse reaction to Johnson & Johnson vaccine to the FDA as required by law.   April 17, 2021 follow up. No new events.  Laboratory studies remained excellent.  White blood count is further elevated, however, this may be secondary to high-dose dexamethasone with a white blood count of 16,060.  Hemoglobin 14.0 g hematocrit 42.8%, MCV 86.8, RDW 12.9%.  Platelet count is actually increased slightly at 374 as of 9:10 AM this morning.  Differential shows left shift as expected with dexamethasone.  Results from yesterday showed fibrinogen normal at 369 (180?415) pro time normal at 10.4 seconds with INR of 0.97, PTT 26.7.  D-dimer 0.23 (0.19?0.50).  With platelet count, fibrinogen and D-dimer normal I am inclined to believe that this is not an acute post vaccination HIT-like phenomena.  If it were I would still expect to see some degree of thrombocytopenia elevated D-dimer and perhaps low fibrinogen.  The other explanations for her cerebral venous sinus thrombosis are either idiopathic spontaneous and merely coincidentally associated at the exact same time as her Covid infection or more likely, cerebral venous sinus thrombosis secondary to hypercoagulable state secondary to her Covid infection from December 2020.  Unfortunatly there is no way to accurately date the acuity of the venous thrombosis in her cerebral sinus.  HIT Testing is still pending and most likely will not be available for 3-4 more days despite being ordered stat.  Have called the laboratory and asked them to check with our outside reference lab what the expected return time is on this test. (LabCorp says "Tuesday April 20, 2021).  Patient refused intravenous gammaglobulin infusion which has been ordered last night.  Patient has been receiving dexamethasone which was a bridge until intravenous gammaglobulin could be administered.  Current guidance from the expert hematology panel (EHP) on Covid vaccine induced thrombosis dated April 7, 2021 from the  public health would state that a patient who has a reduced platelet count without thrombosis with a D-dimer normal and normal fibrinogen or thrombosis with a normal platelet count and D-dimer normal and normal fibrinogen are "unlikely cases".  They recommend for probable cases who have D-dimers that are elevated to send HIT assay and then give immediate intravenous gammaglobulin while awaiting results.  They recommend fibrinogen supplementation, if needed.  They recommend a direct acting antithrombin agents such as the Eliquis this patient is receiving.  They recommend steroids particularly if there is a delay in getting intravenous gammaglobulin delivered.  With the fact that we now have 24 hours in the hospital with no evidence of thrombocytopenia, no evidence of increased fibrinolytic activity or active thrombosis, and no evidence of hypofibrinogenemia, I would argue that her presentation is subacute.  In this setting, I do not feel intravenous gammaglobulin would be necessary and does involve a small risk as well as considerable cost.  Dexamethasone also involves small risk and negligible cost. I have discontinued both of these medications.  My overall impression would be that this was not related to her Johnson & Johnson vaccination which was recent, but rather her more distant Covid infection.  It is impossible to definitively answer the question however.  The next question is duration of anticoagulation.  Risk of recurrent cerebral sinus venous thrombosis is relatively small but the morbidity can be high.  Studies have been performed showing medications in the same class as Eliquis have been associated with a decrease in incidence of the recurrence.  Most hematologist recommend 3 months of anticoagulation for provoked venous thrombosis including cerebral sinus venous thrombosis.  I feel this patient's thrombosis is "provoked", with her association at the same time of her Covid infection (and possibly vaccination).  I would recommend Eliquis (apixaban) 5 mg twice daily or Xarelto (rivaroxaban) 20 mg daily with food. I would feel comfortable in discharging patient for outpatient follow up IF Dr and other speciality services agree. Plan 3 months of full dose anticoagulation with direct factor X inhibitor.   Circulation 2010 Jun 29;121(25):2740-6 "Long-term evaluation of the risk of recurrence after cerebral sinus-venous thrombosis", Background: The clinical course of cerebral sinus-venous thrombosis (CSVT) is largely unknown because prospective studies with a long follow-up and with the goal to assess thrombosis recurrence rate and predisposing factors for recurrence are lacking. Methods and results: One hundred forty-five patients with a first CSVT were followed up for a median of 6 years after discontinuation of anticoagulant treatment. End points were recurrent CSVT or other clinical manifestations of venous thromboembolism. CSVT recurred in 5 patients (3%) and other manifestations of venous thromboembolism (deep vein thrombosis of the lower limbs or pulmonary embolism) were seen in 10 additional patients (7%), for a recurrence rate of 2.03 per 100 person-years (95% confidence interval, 1.16 to 3.14) for all manifestations of venous thromboembolism and 0.53 per 100 person-years (95% confidence interval, 0.16 to 1.10) for CSVT. Nearly half of the recurrences occurred within the first year after discontinuation of anticoagulant therapy. Risk factors for recurrent venous thrombosis were male sex (adjusted hazard ratio, 9.66; 95% confidence interval, 2.86 to 32.7) and, for thromboses other than CSVT, severe thrombophilia resulting from antithrombin, protein C, protein S deficiency, anti-phospholipid antibodies, or combined abnormalities (adjusted hazard ratio, 4.71; 95% confidence interval, 1.34 to 16.5). Conclusions: The risk of recurrent CSVT is low and is higher in the first year after discontinuation of anticoagulant treatment and among men. Mild thrombophilia abnormalities are not associated with recurrent CSVT, but severe thrombophilia entails an increased risk of deep vein thrombosis of the lower limbs or pulmonary embolism.   April 19, 2021 Follow up, no change in condition. Discussed case with Dr, will order Factor V Leiden, prothrombin gene mutation, anti phospholipid and anti cardiolipin antibodies, if she will allow draw. Expect Heparin Induced Thrombosis testing result tomorrow, but with no thrombocytopenia after given heparin, expect will be normal. Will await result. If discharged, would recommend 3 months direct thrombin inhibitor (Eliquis/Xarelto/Pradaxa) at full anticoagulation dose. Then stop, no taper. Overall still feel "provoked" thrombosis due to December Covid, unrelated to J&J Covid vaccine, but can not definitively prove that..

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1) I've had a throbbing pain in my left, frozen shoulder as of early morning the day after receiving the 2nd COVID shot. All progress I had made since an x-ray guided cortisone injection on February 16th followed by weekly PT since is gone.  I was awoken during the night with extreme pain in my shoulder several nights in a row after receiving the 2nd COVID shot. The throbbing pain has started to decrease, but it still comes multiple times each day. I saw Dr. for a scheduled follow-up visit for my cortisone injection today and he confirmed that my shoulder is back to where we started 3 months ago. I have had some joint pain in my right shoulder as well, but not nearly to the extreme pain in my left shoulder. I attribute this to the COVID vaccine as I was making steady progress until I received the 2nd shot. I still wake several times each night due to the pain in my shoulder, but I have not had a throbbing pain wake me in a few days. 2) I also had a  large (golf ball-sized), red, hot lump at the injection site beginning the day after the shot. The redness spread Fri-Sat and Sat-Sun before starting to lessen in redness and heat. The heat and redness were mostly gone by Wednesday (6 days post-injection). I had the nurse at the school where I work look at my arm on the Monday after I received the shot. She agreed that it appeared to be getting less red and less hot.
OTHER_MEDS: metoprolol ER 25 mg synthroid 75 mcg sertraline 75 mg
PRIOR_VAX: smaller, red lump in arm following flu vaccine in December 2020

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I began to feel numb around my mouth and nose.  It spread to most of my face, then chest, then arms, mainly left arm and leg, then to both legs.  General weird feeling / numbness, no pain.  I had trouble with limb control, not bad, but enough to notice. Mainly left side, but noticeable  on both sides.  From the onset on face numbness to the chest leg spread was just a matter of a few, maybe 5 minutes.  I looked at my face in the car mirror, and appeared to have facial control.  I was driving to a relatives house, and it worried me. On the way, I also noticed a lump in my right neck, about the size of a pea.  When I got to my relatives house I told them I thought I had a small stroke, but wasn't sure. The numbness lasted until the next day, then slowly went away.  It took about 2 days before the numb twitchy feeling went away from my left eye/upper cheek area.  The lump in my neck also went away.  rubbing on it actually made the numbness slightly go away. I did not go to a hospital, or seek any treatment.  I think I should have.   I do believe that l had a small stroke / blood clot, and that it should be reported.  I think I am OK now,

On Monday, 4/12/21, I was given the 2nd dose of the vaccine.  There were no immediate symptoms other than a sore arm (from injection site) later that day.  Tuesday morning, my left arm was swollen and I experience joint pain in my fingers and wrist. The following afternoon, I began to feel extremely tired and had vertigo.  I laid down and slept the entire evening; still feeling the joint pain.  The following Wednesday morning, I woke up to a swollen arm with a knot at the injection site, blisters, body rashes, and whelps under my breast and whelps on my shoulder, legs, and feet.  I was even more exhausted. I took Benadryl for the rash and Advil for the pain.  Thursday, I continued to develop rashes that would come and go on the left side of my body and upper chest.  Friday, still experiencing the inflammation and pain, I visited my doctor who told me to continue taking the Benadryl and OTC pain meds.  For good measure, we ordered a d-dimer test.  Over the weekend, in addition to the other symptoms, I began to have a lot or ringing in my ears, a backache (throbbing sensation), and my hands began to painfully swell with blisters.  I could only taste the salt or sugar in foods and was extremely tired.  Monday morning, I received a call from my doctor advising me that the d-dimer test came back extremely high (1.23) and needed to have a vascular ultrasound to check for blood clots.  I visited an ER and had the test done.  No clots were found but I continue to experience ringing in my ears, severe pain in my back that limits my ability to walk and breathe, swelling of various extremities, a rash (and itching), and overall inflammation. The Benadryl isn?t working nor is the OTC pain medication. My doctor has prescribed Prednisone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: EMS was called, because patient began to feel dizzy and extremely nauseous within about 1 minute of being vaccinated. She stood up to walk, but did not get more than 10 feet away before returning to sit down. Her face became flushed. Her BP was high at 177/87 with a pulse of 108, and she complained of having blurry vision. Her blood pressure lowered to 132/90 with a pulse of 82. Her final readings were BP 139/75 and pulse 77 when EMS took them. EMS was called at 1:22pm and arrived at 1:32pm. Pt was given some water and advised to get some rest at home. She refused to ride to the hospital with EMS, and claimed to feel better after another 10-15 minutes or so. EMS thought it was just an anxiety attack.
Vaccine administered ~16 hours after vial punctured from the evening prior, past the recommended 12 hour BUD time limit. No adverse effects noted.

The next morning my eyes were sensitive to light and then I became more exhausted by the hour. Full body Aches set in, foggy head, headache. By around two I began running a light fever. By about 3 pm I felt overall horrible. By four-five I became incredibly nauseated and began vomiting about an hour later. I kept vomiting throughout the night until it was only acidic bile left. During this time I was burning up if I had even a sheet on my skin, but freezing if I didn?t. I was sweating late into the night.  Vomiting stopped around 3 am.   The next two days I managed rice, bananas and teaspoons of water but was always nauseated. Fever was gone, but headache and exhaustion remained.  Daily nausea finally began to wane and was replaced by heartburn and gross feeling in my throat for about two days. About a week and half after the shot I finally regained my energy and had no stomach issues. Two weeks after injection today- The injection site still is bruised and burns/itches from time to time lightly.
LAB_DATA: I wrote my doctor a week in and she said to ride it out and come in if it got worse.
ALLERGIES: None. Celiac disease so can?t eat gluten

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 48 hours after the vaccine my mouth began itching after eating. It happened during breakfast and lunch this day, and then the next morning at breakfast, which is when I became worried. My throat began feeling tight, felt like it had mucus in it and I needed to clear it. My mouth was itching and my tongue felt tingly. Four days after the vaccine my tongue started to swell so I called my doctor.   I saw him the Tuesday, 3/2 after the vaccine and he said my thyroid was swollen and felt I was having an allergic reaction to the vaccine. He did an allergy panel and lab work for my thyroid, all tests came back within normal limits. He referred me to an allergist and said to take benadryl every six hours. A few days later my  bottom lip started to swell and my tongue ached. I was also having intermittent chest pains for about five weeks. Then my lymph nodes in my throat started throbbing.   I saw the allergist on 4/6 and he advised to cancel the second dose. He did lab work to check for autoimmune disorders and inflammation but tests came back normal. He advised on 4/19 to take allegra two times a day for three weeks and we will follow up.   Ongoing symptoms are mouth itching after eating, tingling in throat, and itching on throat and neck, and on and off swelling of my bottom lip. I have also experienced lightheadedness and ocular migraines.
LAB_DATA: 3/4 Blood work for food and environmental allergies and thyroid conditions - labs were normal, allergic to walnuts 4/6 Skin tests for 14 common food allergies - positive to pecans 4/7 Blood work for autoimmune disorders and inflammation - labs were normal
HISTORY: Irritable bowl syndrome, ocular migraines, recently diagnosed with minor thalaseemia

I received my 1st vaccine shot on 04.09.21 at 4:05pm CST. Around 5:15pm CST, my lower extremities and entire left side went numb. All feeling in my lower extremities returned by 11:00 pm CST. The facial and left arm/hand numbness remained with varying degrees of transient numbness. The numbness has ranged from 10% to 95% of feeling. I started doing research and determined my reaction was temporary and inflammatory and Bell Palsy like in nature. I missed work on 04.13.21 and notified my primary care physician, Dr by phone about the numbness. I was informed to go to the ER, especially if the numbness worsened. After taking Benadryl, by morning, the numbness remained transient, but subsided a bit. On 04.17.21, I started to feel a pull on my left eye muscle and a glare when I looked down. I notified my eye doctor, Dr  I underwent an exam.  My eye nerve was fine, however, my prescription in the left eye increased.  As of today, 04.20.21, I am MUCH better, but the injection site remains little sore. The numbness remains transient in my left arm/hand, facial cheeks, and forehead with about 95% of feeling. My skin on my face (T-zones), also feels like sandpaper. I am making this report because I am apprehensive about receiving the 2nd shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On April 18th around 12:15 I was scratching my right thigh, when I looked a notices some red bumps (rash).  I stopped scratching it since I didn't want to irritate it.  I then noticed the rash forming on my left thigh and eventually to my stomach.  It looked like hives so I thought it may be an allergic reactions but I didn't know for sure.  The back of both hands eventually started to feel warm and started to turn red and eventually showed what almost looked like welts.  I again didn't scratch any of the rash and eventually in the evening they disappeared and there was not a trace of the bumps or redness.   When I woke up on April 19th, I immediately checked to make sure the rash was gone and it was.  As the morning progressed I noticed a burning sensation on the back of both my hands, both my legs and feet, stomach and the left and right side of my waste.  I was concerned and immediately started checking online about the possible side effects of the vaccine.  Both of my feet were so red that my toes looked almost blue/purple and both my legs were covered in red spots which looked almost like the measles or the shingles.  I called my doctor to try and get an appointment but she didn't have anything available.  By the end of the day,  the rash was gone and again there was no trace that they were ever there except for the pictures that I took.   On the morning of April 20th, I again checked to see if there was any sign of the rash and thankfully there was none.  As the day progressed I noticed a burning sensation on both my elbows and forearm areas and there it was again.  The rash was also on both of my knees but not as bad the the previous day.  As the day progressed, the rash again disappeared without a trace.  By evening I noticed my hands were irritated and  I saw red bumps again but not as bad.  I also noticed the bumps returned to both my knees and around my feet.  This is very uncomfortable and I hope they finally go away for good but the fact that they keep coming back has me concerned since I am scheduled to receive my 2nd dose of Pfizer on April 27th and I'm not sure if I should get it since I don't want to aggravate my current rash.

Patient was observed post Covid-19 immunization for 15 minutes .  During the observation period, he experienced an adverse reaction with the following symptoms:  nausea and vomiting.   Assessment : Time of assessment 1005. Alert and oriented, Anxious, Tachycardia, Nausea, Emesis and left hand tingling. As soon as patient received vaccine and was getting ready to sit for his 15 minute observation, he started vomiting x 1 in the floor. He says he felt nauseated, lightheaded, and his left hand was tingling. He was assisted in the wheelchair and taken to the triage area.  1012: BP 148/100, P 110, denies nausea, lightheaded, but still has the tingling to the left hand. 1017: BP 138/100, P 102, denies hand tingling or any other symptoms. 1026 standing BP 120/88, P 108.    Actions taken:  Vitals sign taken  VAERS form obtained and completed by RN. Ambulated prior to discharge home without symptoms.   There were no vitals filed for this visit.   Medications administered: No medication administered.   Disposition: Reports no further symptoms of adverse reaction after observation for 20 minutes. Discharged home. Instructed to call 911 for trouble breathing, rapid heart rate, dizziness, swelling of tongue or throat. The Patient was provided with Vaccine Information Sheet and instruction to access the V-Safe system.

numbness from left pinky finger to wrist/numbness on the bottom of right site of right foot and moved up to the ankle; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness from left pinky finger to wrist/numbness on the bottom of right site of right foot and moved up to the ankle) in a 52-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 030L20A) for COVID-19 vaccination.     Concurrent medical conditions included Shoulder soreness (right). Concomitant products included MELOXICAM for Shoulder soreness, SPIRONOLACTONE and VITAMINS NOS for an unknown indication.    On 28-Jan-2021 at 10:30 AM, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 28-Jan-2021 at 10:45 AM, the patient experienced HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness from left pinky finger to wrist/numbness on the bottom of right site of right foot and moved up to the ankle) (seriousness criterion disability). At the time of the report, HYPOAESTHESIA (numbness from left pinky finger to wrist/numbness on the bottom of right site of right foot and moved up to the ankle) had not resolved.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown.       On 28 Jan 2021, the patient did not take her concomitant medications because she was about to receive the vaccine.   The patient did not take any medicine to treat the event. At the time of the report, the numbness was still there but no pain.  This case concerns a 52-year-old female with a serious unexpected event of hypoaesthesia. Event onset 15 minutes after first dose mRNA-1273. Event ongoing. Based on current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns a 52-year-old female with a serious unexpected event of hypoaesthesia. Event onset 15 minutes after first dose mRNA-1273. Event ongoing. Based on current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

COVID-19 pneumonia; Weakness; This spontaneous case was reported by a patient family member or friend (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of COVID-19 PNEUMONIA (COVID-19 pneumonia) and ASTHENIA (Weakness) in an 83-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 002A21A and 030L20A) for COVID-19 vaccination.     The patient's past medical history included Artificial cardiac pacemaker user and COVID-19 on 01-Feb-2021. Concurrent medical conditions included Chronic kidney disease (20 years). SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up in the middle of the first night after receiving 2nd dose of Moderna.  I had a fever, chills and muscle aches, and extreme fatigue.  Those symptoms lasted approx 3 days.  Two days after the vaccination I also became extremely nauseous.  I was anticipating all of these symptoms.  On the 3rd and 4th days after the vaccine most of the symptoms disappeared but I received some new ones that I was not expecting.  I suddenly felt a large amount of despair and hopelessness.  I had suicidal thoughts.  I had panic attacks and anxiety.  I had paranoia.  I did not feel like I had long to live, or anything to live for.  By 20 Apr all of these emotional and mental side effects were completely gone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am 3 months post partum. The day after  I received my shot, my pelvic area had a odd feeling. Almost like my uterus felt a dull very very mild pressure. Day 2 after receiving my shot, I started to bleed. I am exclusively breastfeeding and I have never had a period start this early with all of my other children. Normal is 7 plus months for me. This period was also not a normal period. I had zero cramps. I felt nothing. I never have had a period with zero cramps. Lasted for 7 days.

Patient got vaccinated at 10:32 AM.   He called at 2:24 PM and said that his hand has been shaking "since 2 hours ago".  He said it's been like that for 1 hour.   He self-reports that he checked his blood glucose & blood pressure and they're all within  normal.  I told him to see MD ASAP.  Last I heard from him was that he's going to call an ambulance.

On April 5th I was sitting, watching TV. Suddenly, it felt as though I needed to pop my left ear and I couldn't. I also couldn't hear out of that ear It was a roaring sound like the ocean and intermittent buzzing and ringing in my ear. The next day was no better and I started getting dizzy. By April 5th I had a very bad case of Vertigo and had to go to the hospital. I was given an IV with motion sickness meds and nausea meds, as well as antibiotics and I think a steroid shot. I still couldn't hear. I was sent home with prescriptions. The vertigo gradually got better over the following days, but I never regained my hearing. On the 12th of April, still feeling the affects of the vertigo, and out of nausea meds, I went to my primary doctor. I received another steroid shot and more meds. On the 19th I went again and got a hearing test. I am deaf in my left ear and will see a specialist.
LAB_DATA: Deaf in left ear. Not sure why.
OTHER_MEDS: Aspirin, Metoprol, Atorvastatin, Diltiazem, zyrtec (as needed for environmental allergies)
HISTORY: Atrial fibrillation due to a valve problem
ALLERGIES: Azithromycin, arithromycin, betadine, sulfa antibiotics, prednisone

Within the next 40 minutes I vomited and had diarrhea. At the time also had body aches, chills, fever, and mild swelling of various areas if the body. I slept most of the morning and ate lunch around 1:30 pm. I took Tylenol again at 2:00 pm with the symptoms lessening over the next 5-6 hours. After that fever, chills, and body aches returned.

As the day went on and I moved around, the hives disappeared. Before going to bed, I noticed that my left eye was mildly swollen. The next morning, I woke up and the hives returned. Again, after moving around, the hives went away. Later in the late afternoon and into the evening, I noticed that both of my eyes were swollen and so was my upper lip. I woke up and the hives returned, only one eye was swollen and my lip was swollen. By later in the afternoon, the hives and swelling had just about disappeared. The following morning, I was back to normal with no hives and no swelling around my eyes or lips.

My lips became numb, then my tongue and the tip of my nose began to tingle.  I took Benadryl about 20 minutes after onset (when I got home), and the tingling stopped within 30 minutes.  The numbness wore off after an hour or so.  I felt normal by evening.  No recurrence.  Headaches that night and over the next day.

On 19-Mar-2021, the patient experienced INAPPROPRIATE SCHEDULE OF PRODUCT ADMINISTRATION (Second dose administered on 38th day). On 23-Mar-2021, the patient experienced RESPIRATORY TRACT IRRITATION (pressure in the area of her cancer (left lung cancer)/felt was like somebody was squeezing her lungs/tightened up in the area of her cancer) (seriousness criterion intervention required), PULMONARY PAIN (painful in the area of her cancer) (seriousness criterion intervention required), DYSPNOEA (difficulty in breathing) (seriousness criterion intervention required) and DISCOMFORT (lot of discomfort). On 27-Mar-2021, the patient experienced ILLNESS (really really sick - with chemotherapy), HYPERTENSION (blood pressure was slightly elevated), MALAISE (felt unusual), PYREXIA (Temperature was 100.4F.) and FATIGUE (exhausted). On 19-Mar-2021, INAPPROPRIATE SCHEDULE OF PRODUCT ADMINISTRATION (Second dose administered on 38th day) had resolved. On 26-Mar-2021, RESPIRATORY TRACT IRRITATION (pressure in the area of her cancer (left lung cancer)/felt was like somebody was squeezing her lungs/tightened up in the area of her cancer), PULMONARY PAIN (painful in the area of her cancer), DYSPNOEA (difficulty in breathing) and DISCOMFORT (lot of discomfort) had resolved. Not Provided          Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter.  Because of chemotherapy the patient rescheduled her second shot and so it was delayed. Few days later (2-3 days) she got really really sick and felt very tired - she was under chemotherapy. This never happened before with the chemotherapy (she has been taking it from several years). Her blood pressure was slightly elevated. Temperature was 100.4F. She felt very unusual and exhausted. All this happened for about for about 4-5 days. wake up in the middle of the right with the pens and needles tingling sensation; becoming tired as the day progressed; herpes presented as cold; patchy with numbness in right hip & thigh; herpes on her right buttock; sensation of pens and needles tingling at the injection site; pens and needles tingling that eventually started to pass into entire right arm, and then moved to right leg; Initial information regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious was received from a Consumer/non-hcp (healthcare professional) via Medical Information (Refnerence number- 00495438).  This case involves a 61 years old female patient who experienced pens and needles tingling that eventually started to pass into entire right arm, and then moved to right leg (paraesthesia), wake up in the middle of the right with the pens and needles tingling sensation (middle insomnia), herpes presented as cold (nasopharyngitis), patchy with numbness in right hip & thigh (hypoaesthesia), herpes on her right buttock (herpes virus infection), becoming tired as the day progressed (fatigue) and sensation of pens and needles tingling at the injection site (vaccination site paraesthesia), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV].  Medical history, past medical treatments, past vaccinations, concomitant medication and family history were not provided.  On 29-Jan-2021, the patient received a first dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE (lot number and expiration date were not reported) via unknown route in right arm for prophylactic vaccination.  On 29-Jan-2021, on same day patient started to experience the sensation of pens and needles tingling at the injection site (vaccination site paraesthesia). As the day progressed and throughout the rest of that day, she continued to have the pens and needles tingling that eventually started to pass into her entire right arm (paraesthesia). After about 2 weeks of these symptoms, the pens and needles tingling continued in her right arm and then moved to her right leg (paraesthesia). The right arm and leg symptoms continued, then. after a few hours, the sensation would go away and return, this continued from around 13-Feb-2021 into the following week. The sensation would return during the night as she would wake up in the middle of the right with the pens and needles tingling sensation (middle insomnia). She was able to get back to sleep, and when she would wake up for the next few days, the sensation would come & go, following the administration of vaccine.   On 18-Feb-2021, after 20 days patient experienced herpes on her right buttock (herpes virus infection), the herpes presented as cold (nasopharyngitis) and patchy with numbness in her right hip & thigh (hypoaesthesia). This continued through 21-Feb-2021, still with the on & off pens and needles tingling presence but was then running from her right hip to her toe and has continued since, following the administration of vaccine.  Patient continued with her normal days exercising with no real discomfort except for the off and on pens and needles tingling and was becoming tired as the day progressed (fatigue) on an unknown date after vaccination.  It was reported that the vaccine the vaccine was quick & painless. Patient never felt weakness or imbalance. Physician suggested that she has an MRI of her brain and did not think that these symptoms have come from taking the Flublok. she plans to see a local neurologist for a consult & MRI (Magnetic resonance imaging).  Relevant laboratory test results included: Patient's blood pressure and reflexes were good.  It was not reported if the patient received any corrective treatment or not.  The patient was recovered from all the events.  There will be no information on the batch number for this case.
LAB_DATA: Test Name: blood pressure; Result Unstructured Data: good

food panel it showed that she had a sensitivity to an egg; chest felt strained like when you are holding your breath swimming under water; trouble seeing; face was swollen like an egg; eyes had a sticky substance in them like Elmer's glue and they were oozing; funny feeling in her chest; cough; Initial information received on 09-Apr-2021 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from a consumer/non-health care professional via Global Media Information (GMI reference number 00555398).  This case involves a 56 years old female patient who experienced chest felt strained like when you are holding your breath swimming under water (chest discomfort); funny feeling in her chest (feeling abnormal) , trouble seeing (visual impairment), face was swollen like an egg (swelling face), eyes had a sticky substance in them like Elmer's glue and they were oozing (eye discharge), cough, after receiving INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B SUBVIRION NO PRESERVATIVE VACCINE [FLUZONE].  Past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s), concomitant medication(s) and family history were not provided.  At the time of the event, the patient was found sensitive to egg (food allergy).  In January 2014, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B SUBVIRION NO PRESERVATIVE VACCINE (0.5 prefilled syringe, lot UH922AB and expiry date not reported) via unknown route in an unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  In January 2014, Patient stated that the reaction she had was not within the first 15 minutes and she said she took her daughter as well and it was in the late afternoon 3:30-4 pm and then probably 2-3 hours later she noticed her chest felt strained like when you are holding your breath swimming under water (chest discomfort). She stated that it started with cough and then she had the funny feeling in her chest (feeling abnormal) and was laying on couch watching tv and had trouble seeing (visual impairment). She also reported that, she was watching a show and then went to the bathroom and saw that her face was swollen like an egg (swelling face) and her eyes had a sticky substance in them like Elmer's glue and they were oozing (eye discharge), so she drove to the ER (emergency room) and she was informed that it was an allergic reaction to the vaccine.  She stated that she eats eggs and did not have a problem but when she did a food panel it showed that she had a sensitivity to an egg (contraindication to vaccination, same day latency).    All the reported events were assessed as serious, as the patient was hospitalized for these events.  She reported that her reaction was not a sore arm.  Hence, reported that caller would like to know the ingredients in the Fluzone vaccine from January 2014 contained eggs, that was Preservative free because she had an above adverse reactions that landed her on the hospital. Also stated that she wanted to do her due diligence now to know the ingredients before she got a Covid (coronavirus disease) vaccine and a flu vaccine because she does not want the same thing to happen again. The caller wanted her son who has cerebral palsy and autism to receive the COVID 19 vaccine and she was not sure if what she experienced was genetic. The caller also stated that she had paperwork and it was a clinic summary they gave her. She states that she was not sure if it was reported as an adverse reaction because her paperwork said it was not submitted so it looked like she had trouble submitting the information.    Other relevant laboratory test were not reported.  It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  At time of reporting, the outcome was unknown for all the reported events.  It was also reported that the patient was looking for information in the DailyMed website that only went back to 03-Aug-2015 in terms of their prescribing information, on what was in the vaccine she received and she would like a call back in regards to this.; Sender's Comments: This case involves a 56 years old female patient who had chest discomfort, feeling abnormal, visual impairment, swelling face, eye discharge and cough, after vaccination with INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B SUBVIRION NO PRESERVATIVE VACCINE. The time to onset is compatible. It was also a case of contraindication to vaccination as the patient was allergic to egg. However, further information on patient's medical condition at the time of vaccination and lab tests were not reported. Based upon the reported information, the role of a vaccine cannot be assessed.
LAB_DATA: Test Name: food panel; Result Unstructured Data: food panel showed that she had a sensitivity to an egg.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient had 2 emergency department visits for this problem.  The first visit the patient presented with urticaria.  The patient was treated with antihistamines (H1 and H2 blockers) and corticosteroids.  He was discharged home on prednisone twice daily and over-the-counter Benadryl.  He represented to the emergency department with worsening of symptoms.  The urticaria were much more diffuse and the patient also had angioedema of the lips.  There was no angioedema of the tongue or throat.  The patient had no wheezing or shortness of breath.  He was treated with H1 and H2 blockers again, IV corticosteroids and IM epinephrine.  The symptoms improved and the patient was discharged on fexofenadine twice daily, famotidine twice daily, the prednisone was increased to daily and hydroxyzine  as needed for breakthrough pruritus or rash.
LAB_DATA: At the time of the first visit the patient had a CBC, BMP, magnesium and phosphorus levels.  His labs were all normal with the exception of a mildly elevated RBC count at 6.14 and hematocrit of 52.6.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Frontal lobe headache to start within a few hrs of vaccine. Back of the head to lower neck headache 8 hrs after. Every tooth in my mouth started throbbing at around 11 hrs  and continued for about 5 more hours. Also during that time, waves of nausea but no vomiting, also uncontrollable shivering but I wasn't cold and I wasn't hot but weird shivering. I did not take my temperature as I didn't feel like I had a fever. Around 13 hrs after a stabbing pain in front of thighs like hot pokers started and around 14 hrs thigh pain was still present but then the calves on both legs started to get the same stabbing pain.   At around 24 hrs after - headache remained, pulsating teeth stopped, thigh pain stopped but calf pain remained. Headache remained off and on for several days. General brain fog also lasted for about 1 week. The calf pain comes and goes even after 2 weeks. Arm where shot was administered was very tender to the touch for the last 2 weeks.   Lastly, I wouldn't say I had shortness of breath but at times I just felt like I needed to stop and force myself to take a very deep breath.
OTHER_MEDS: no RXs, no OTC, only vitamins - C, D3, CQ10, A, D, K, B Complex, Magnesium, Zinc
CUR_ILL: No illnesses at the time nor up to one month prior - no illnesses over 2 years.
ALLERGIES: Only reaction is to generic Vicodin (extreme nausea) and a very old drug - Declomycin taken when I was about 8 yrs old - developed a rash.

Immediately had flu symptoms the same night as vaccine that went away within 2 days. HOWEVER,  twenty-one (21) days later, both eyes were extremely painful to move. Then I lost vision in right eye with extreme blurriness & partial blind spots resulting in a diagnosis of Optic Neuritis by Ophthalmologist and Neurologist. Confirmed optic Neuritis on MRI scan.  Twenty-four (24) days later, numbness in legs, feet and right arm started. Hard to walk up and down stairs. Twenty-six (26) days later, extreme pain in in muscles and skin along with tingles all over and numbness. Weakness and Chest pain. Flu like symptoms without fever ie: aches, pains, skin pain, confusion. Dizziness, feeling of being extremely anxious and out of sorts in space. Had to complete round of Steroids and numbness and tingles got better, but did not dissolve. After completion of IV steroids, thirty-four (34) days later all symptoms returned full force and worsening. Checked into ER 4/10 and admitted into hospital. Have not been able to complete normal routine or work level since March 27th due to neurological disturbance and symptoms.   Two (2) Eye exams, 3/30/21 confirming swollen optic nerves.  MRI 3/31/21 Blood work 4/2/21 CoVid Test 4/9/21 Negative  Hospital: April 10-12th.  MRI Extensive Blood work Spinal Tap Neuro-Opt exam  Outcome pending and further treatment pending results.

25 yo G2P0 @ 37+1 pregnant with longstanding immune thrombocytopenia purpura with a routine CBC showing PLTs of 56 down from 119 1 month ago. Had J&J vaccine on 4/9.    - Lab repeated and confirmed - D/w MFM and Hematologist.  In an abundance of caution, will get coags, CMP, and P/cr urine ratio to evaluate for HELLP.  Will also get HIT antibodies to evaluate for possibility of Vaccine induced thrombocytopenia(VIT). - Will plan on treating with Dexamethasone 40mg Daily x 4 days to increase platelet count.  D/w hematologist, and he will see the patient and run the test for HIT antibodies (PF-4) and initiate IVIG treatment, which would help treat the low platelets either from exacerbation of ITP or VIT. If these come back positive, will likely transfer patient to HN for admission and delivery to be followed by therapeutic anticoagulation with non-heparin based therapy, consistent with usual therapy for HIT.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started with a fever, chills and just general flu like symptoms that started the day of my 2nd vaccination(3/25/21) all which I knew I may experience. These started around 9pm on Thursday evening, and subsided by 6pm on Friday 3/26/21. On Saturday 3/27/21 I started to feel pain in my lower back. It wasn?t pain in the muscles it was itching of the skin that turned into a piercing pain that covered my lower back. I contacted my primary care and she said it sounded like shingles and asked if I had a rash. I did not. She started me on Gabapentin 300mg 1 capsule by mouth 3x a day as needed for pain. The symptoms lasted until approximately the evening of Tuesday 3/30/21. No rash ever appeared but the burning/itching/piercing pain is what stayed with me for those 3 days.
OTHER_MEDS: None at the time of vaccination

Around 4:00 pm on 4/12/2021 I began to feel a slight headache and my side effects worsened that evening. I lost my appetite due to the muscle pain, aches, fatigue, and chills that I felt. After taking a nap, I did not feel rested but instead restless. Because of the chills, I put on joggers and a sweatshirt, then proceeded to try and read a book while sitting under a blanket. I was unable to concentrate or focus on my book because of the chills, so I instead watched television. By 9:00 pm, I tried to go to sleep and took my last remaining dose of Tylenol. The aches and chills had only gotten worse and I was still dressed in joggers and sweatshirt as I tried to fall asleep underneath two blankets and quilt. All night long I tossed and turned because of the shivers, aches, and chills. I was unable to sleep for more than 45 to 60 minutes at a time before I woke up again. This happened repeatedly all night and it was very painful. On 4/13/2021 around 8:00 am, I got out of bed with continued shivers, aches, pain, fatigue, headache, and chills. I suffered from these symptoms all day long. Around 3:00 pm I tried to eat spaghetti with meatballs and steamed vegetables, but the spaghetti tasted like cardboard and I was only able to eat come of the vegetable mix. All day long I kept drinking water to stay hydrated and spent most of my time switching from my couch to my bed with restlessness, aches, shivers, and chills. The chills started to subside around 2:00 am on 4/14/2021 after I took a hot shower for about 15 to 20 minutes. Still dressed in joggers and a sweatshirt, this time I tried to sleep under two blankets, but the shivers and chills kept waking me up every 60 to 90 minutes. On 4/14/2021 around 10:00 am, I finally felt well enough to be able to drive to a store to by ibuprofen. When I got home, I took some and was finally able to take a nap and get some rest. I felt much better after my nap, was able to eat, and go for a small walk. This was my Pfizer second shot and it is worth mentioning that I live alone with no friends or family and I am an COVID-19. I had nobody to call and ask for help or to take care of me. I had to deal with the additional psychological trauma of not being able to ask anyone for help as I worried how long the adverse effects would last. I did not call my doctor because the last time I went in to see him, the facility charged me $170 for a 20-minute appointment and decided to take more than two months to let me know that I still owed $119. Everyone at the CDC and other agencies have failed those of us who live alone, especially public health officials, who did absolutely nothing to prepare to help and support people like me during this pandemic. Your ideals of individualism are bad public health policy for those of us who are alone, have nobody to turn do, and do all the right things by wearing masks, getting vaccinated, and staying six feet away from everybody. Yet, we are the ones who suffer the most and have to struggle with adverse effects of pandemic trauma, depression, and other mental health issues in addition to loss of taste and smell. I have not enjoyed food in over six months. It sure would be nice if for the next pandemic you also put together a plan for people who live alone and have nobody to turn to for help because you've failed us in this pandemic.
Severe dizziness went bending ormoving head and feelings of vertigo head down, 2 days after 2nd vaccination shot No rash, no swelling

HISTORY: I discovered at age seventy that I had bipolar disorder I. When I learned, following a bipolar episode that I had a genetically predisposed condition to bipolar disorder (on my mother's side of the family), I studied the condition and its effect on my life for more than five years, first accepting and acknowledging the condition, then exploring its presence in my life and its effects on my life and others. I am currently writing a book on the subject and the sources of the disorder which trigger episodes. I have been without any symptoms for over five years and feel confident that there will be none as a result of knowledge, insight and behavioral changes. My question is whether questionnaires for potential vaccine recipients included any questions about mental health conditions or symptoms. I don't recall any and am trying to discover whether the symptoms I have had following the vaccination with Moderna 13 days ago could be related to a psychological disorder or to the vaccine. I have been well, happy and productive for the last five years and am puzzled why sleeplessness, fatigue and nightmares have suddenly appeared following the first covid vaccination.
